<div class="tag">SAT Math · Module 4 · Lesson 4.7</div>
<div class="lesson-title">Trigonometry</div>
<div class="lesson-sub">Master SOH-CAH-TOA, the key trigonometric identities the SAT tests, and the complementary angle relationship — the single most tested trig concept on the current digital SAT.</div>
<div class="dur-row"><span><b>13 min</b> read</span><span><b>3</b> practice questions</span><span><b>+20 pts</b> on completion</span></div>

<div class="card">
  <div class="sec-title">SOH-CAH-TOA — the three ratios</div>
  <div class="body-text">For a right triangle with a reference angle θ, the three trigonometric ratios relate the angle to the sides of the triangle. Always label: <strong>opposite</strong> (side across from θ), <strong>adjacent</strong> (side next to θ, not hypotenuse), and <strong>hypotenuse</strong> (longest side, across from 90°).</div>
  <div class="soh-box">
    <div class="soh-item">
      <div class="soh-label">SOH</div>
      <div class="soh-def">sin θ = opp/hyp</div>
      <div class="soh-expand">Sine = Opposite over Hypotenuse</div>
    </div>
    <div class="soh-item">
      <div class="soh-label">CAH</div>
      <div class="soh-def">cos θ = adj/hyp</div>
      <div class="soh-expand">Cosine = Adjacent over Hypotenuse</div>
    </div>
    <div class="soh-item">
      <div class="soh-label">TOA</div>
      <div class="soh-def">tan θ = opp/adj</div>
      <div class="soh-expand">Tangent = Opposite over Adjacent</div>
    </div>
  </div>
</div>

<div class="card">
  <div class="sec-title">Key identities and relationships</div>
  <div class="identity-grid">
    <div class="id-card">
      <div class="id-title">Complementary angle identity ← most tested</div>
      <div class="id-formula">sin θ = cos(90° − θ)<br>cos θ = sin(90° − θ)</div>
      <div class="id-note">In a right triangle, if one acute angle is θ, the other is (90°−θ). The sine of one equals the cosine of the other. The SAT uses this constantly.</div>
    </div>
    <div class="id-card">
      <div class="id-title">Pythagorean identity</div>
      <div class="id-formula">sin²θ + cos²θ = 1</div>
      <div class="id-note">Always true for any angle. Useful for finding sin given cos (or vice versa) without finding the angle itself.</div>
    </div>
    <div class="id-card">
      <div class="id-title">Tangent identity</div>
      <div class="id-formula">tan θ = sin θ / cos θ</div>
      <div class="id-note">Tangent equals opposite/adjacent, which equals (opp/hyp) ÷ (adj/hyp) = sin/cos.</div>
    </div>
    <div class="id-card">
      <div class="id-title">Reciprocal relationships</div>
      <div class="id-formula">1/sin θ = csc θ<br>1/cos θ = sec θ<br>1/tan θ = cot θ</div>
      <div class="id-note">The SAT rarely tests these directly, but recognizing them helps simplify expressions.</div>
    </div>
  </div>
  <div class="example-box">
    <div class="example-label">Worked example — complementary angles</div>
    <div class="example-text">
      In a right triangle, sin(x°) = 4/5. What is cos(90° − x°)?<br><br>
      <span class="fb-work">By the complementary angle identity: cos(90° − x°) = sin(x°)</span><br>
      <span class="fb-work">Therefore cos(90° − x°) = 4/5</span><br><br>
      No calculation needed — just recognize the identity. This is the most common trig question format on the SAT.
    </div>
  </div>
  <div class="example-box" style="margin-top:.75rem">
    <div class="example-label">Worked example — finding a side using trig</div>
    <div class="example-text">
      A ladder leans against a wall, making a 65° angle with the ground. The ladder is 10 meters long. How high up the wall does it reach?<br><br>
      <span class="fb-work">The height is opposite to 65°; the ladder (10m) is the hypotenuse.</span><br>
      <span class="fb-work">sin(65°) = opposite/hypotenuse = h/10</span><br>
      <span class="fb-work">h = 10 × sin(65°) ≈ 10 × 0.906 ≈ 9.06 meters</span>
    </div>
  </div>
</div>

<div class="card">
  <div class="sec-title">SAT strategy tips</div>
  <div class="tips-grid">
    <div class="tip"><div class="tip-title">Label sides before writing ratios</div><div class="tip-body">Before using SOH-CAH-TOA, always label which side is opposite, adjacent, and the hypotenuse relative to your reference angle θ. Mislabeling is the most common trig error.</div></div>
    <div class="tip"><div class="tip-title">sin(x) = cos(90−x) is on every SAT</div><div class="tip-body">The SAT always tests the complementary angle relationship. If sin(A) = cos(B), then A + B = 90°. If sin(x°) = cos(32°), then x + 32 = 90, so x = 58. This takes 5 seconds once you know it.</div></div>
    <div class="tip"><div class="tip-title">Use the calculator correctly for trig</div><div class="tip-body">Make sure your calculator is in DEGREE mode (not radian) for SAT problems. To find an angle: use inverse trig — sin⁻¹, cos⁻¹, tan⁻¹. To find a side: use the ratio directly.</div></div>
    <div class="tip"><div class="tip-title">Trig with the Pythagorean identity</div><div class="tip-body">If sin θ = 3/5, find cos θ: sin²θ + cos²θ = 1 → 9/25 + cos²θ = 1 → cos²θ = 16/25 → cos θ = 4/5. This avoids finding the angle — just work with the ratios directly.</div></div>
  </div>
</div>

<div class="sec-title" style="margin-bottom:.75rem">Practice questions</div>
