<div class="lesson-title">Circles</div>
<div class="lesson-sub">Master the standard equation of a circle, arc length, sector area, inscribed angles, and the key circle theorems the SAT tests — all in the coordinate plane.</div>
<div class="dur-row"><span><b>13 min</b> read</span><span><b>3</b> practice questions</span><span><b>+20 pts</b> on completion</span></div>

<div class="card">
  <div class="sec-title">Circle equations and properties</div>
  <div class="formula-grid">
    <div class="f-card">
      <div class="f-title">Standard equation of a circle</div>
      <div class="f-eq">(x − h)² + (y − k)² = r²</div>
      <div class="f-note">Center = (h, k) · Radius = r. Watch signs: (x − 3)² has center x = 3, not −3.</div>
    </div>
    <div class="f-card">
      <div class="f-title">Arc length & sector area</div>
      <div class="f-eq">Arc = (θ/360) · 2πr<br>Sector = (θ/360) · πr²</div>
      <div class="f-note">θ = central angle in degrees. Both are fractions of the full circle.</div>
    </div>
    <div class="f-card">
      <div class="f-title">Inscribed angle theorem</div>
      <div class="f-eq">Inscribed angle = ½ · central angle</div>
      <div class="f-note">An inscribed angle is half the central angle that subtends the same arc.</div>
    </div>
    <div class="f-card">
      <div class="f-title">Tangent line to circle</div>
      <div class="f-eq">Tangent ⊥ radius at point of tangency</div>
      <div class="f-note">A tangent line is perpendicular to the radius drawn to the point of contact. Use Pythagorean theorem for tangent length problems.</div>
    </div>
    <div class="f-card">
      <div class="f-title">Completing the square</div>
      <div class="f-eq">x² + y² + Dx + Ey + F = 0</div>
      <div class="f-note">Group x and y terms, complete the square on each group to find center and radius.</div>
    </div>
    <div class="f-card">
      <div class="f-title">Semicircle inscribed angle</div>
      <div class="f-eq">Angle in semicircle = 90°</div>
      <div class="f-note">Any angle inscribed in a semicircle (with the diameter as its side) is always a right angle.</div>
    </div>
  </div>
  <div class="example-box">
    <div class="example-label">Worked example — completing the square</div>
    <div class="example-text">
      Find the center and radius of: x² + y² − 6x + 4y − 3 = 0<br><br>
      <span class="fb-work">Group: (x² − 6x) + (y² + 4y) = 3</span><br>
      <span class="fb-work">Complete: (x² − 6x + 9) + (y² + 4y + 4) = 3 + 9 + 4</span><br>
      <span class="fb-work">(x − 3)² + (y + 2)² = 16</span><br>
      Center: (3, −2) · Radius: 4
    </div>
  </div>
</div>

<div class="card">
  <div class="sec-title">SAT strategy tips</div>
  <div class="tips-grid">
    <div class="tip"><div class="tip-title">Center sign trap — always check</div><div class="tip-body">(x − 3)² + (y + 5)² = 49 has center (3, −5) — NOT (−3, 5). The signs in the equation are opposite to the center coordinates. Rewrite (y + 5)² as (y − (−5))² to see it clearly.</div></div>
    <div class="tip"><div class="tip-title">Completing the square for general form</div><div class="tip-body">When the circle equation is expanded (x² + y² + Dx + Ey = F), complete the square. Add (D/2)² and (E/2)² to both sides. The right side becomes the radius squared.</div></div>
    <div class="tip"><div class="tip-title">Inscribed angle = half the arc it intercepts</div><div class="tip-body">An inscribed angle equals half the central angle subtending the same arc. If the arc is 80°, the inscribed angle is 40°. A diameter subtends a 180° arc — so any inscribed angle on a diameter = 90°.</div></div>
    <div class="tip"><div class="tip-title">Tangent + radius = right angle</div><div class="tip-body">When a tangent meets a radius, they form a 90° angle. Draw this right angle and use the Pythagorean theorem to find tangent length, if given the radius and distance from center to external point.</div></div>
  </div>
</div>

