<div class="lesson-title">Volume & 3D Geometry</div>
<div class="lesson-sub">Master volume formulas for all 3D shapes on the SAT, learn to work with cross-sections, and solve density and rate-of-fill problems that use volume in context.</div>
<div class="dur-row"><span><b>12 min</b> read</span><span><b>3</b> practice questions</span><span><b>+20 pts</b> on completion</span></div>

<div class="card">
  <div class="sec-title">Volume formulas — all shapes on the SAT</div>
  <div class="vol-grid">
    <div class="vol-card">
      <div class="vol-shape">Rectangular prism (box)</div>
      <div class="vol-eq">V = lwh</div>
      <div class="vol-note">l = length, w = width, h = height. Surface area = 2(lw + lh + wh).</div>
    </div>
    <div class="vol-card">
      <div class="vol-shape">Cylinder</div>
      <div class="vol-eq">V = πr²h</div>
      <div class="vol-note">r = radius of circular base, h = height. Same as circle area × height.</div>
    </div>
    <div class="vol-card">
      <div class="vol-shape">Cone</div>
      <div class="vol-eq">V = ⅓πr²h</div>
      <div class="vol-note">Exactly ⅓ of the cylinder with same base and height. h = perpendicular height.</div>
    </div>
    <div class="vol-card">
      <div class="vol-shape">Sphere</div>
      <div class="vol-eq">V = (4/3)πr³</div>
      <div class="vol-note">Surface area = 4πr². Note: volume uses r cubed, surface area uses r squared.</div>
    </div>
    <div class="vol-card">
      <div class="vol-shape">Pyramid</div>
      <div class="vol-eq">V = ⅓ × base area × h</div>
      <div class="vol-note">Any pyramid: ⅓ of the prism with same base. Base area depends on shape of base.</div>
    </div>
    <div class="vol-card">
      <div class="vol-shape">Density relationship</div>
      <div class="vol-eq">Density = mass/volume<br>mass = density × volume</div>
      <div class="vol-note">Common SAT application: find mass given density and dimensions, or find a dimension given mass and density.</div>
    </div>
  </div>
  <div class="example-box">
    <div class="example-label">Worked example — volume and density</div>
    <div class="example-text">
      A cylindrical tank has radius 3 m and height 8 m. Water (density 1,000 kg/m³) fills it at 2 m³/minute. How long to fill it completely?<br><br>
      <span class="fb-work">Volume = π(3)²(8) = 72π ≈ 226.2 m³</span><br>
      <span class="fb-work">Time = Volume ÷ Rate = 226.2 ÷ 2 ≈ 113.1 minutes</span>
    </div>
  </div>
</div>

<div class="card">
  <div class="sec-title">SAT strategy tips</div>
  <div class="tips-grid">
    <div class="tip"><div class="tip-title">Cone and pyramid: always multiply by ⅓</div><div class="tip-body">Both cones and pyramids have volume = ⅓ × base × height. The ⅓ is the most commonly forgotten factor. A cone is exactly ⅓ of its surrounding cylinder; a pyramid is ⅓ of its surrounding prism.</div></div>
    <div class="tip"><div class="tip-title">Scale factor for similar 3D shapes</div><div class="tip-body">If linear dimensions scale by factor k, volume scales by k³. If a sphere's radius doubles, its volume is 2³ = 8 times larger. The SAT tests this frequently in "how many times greater" questions.</div></div>
    <div class="tip"><div class="tip-title">Cross-section problems</div><div class="tip-body">A cross-section is the 2D shape you see when slicing through a 3D solid. A vertical slice through a cylinder = rectangle. A horizontal slice = circle. Knowing cross-sections helps with volume calculations.</div></div>
    <div class="tip"><div class="tip-title">Units matter — watch cubic vs. square</div><div class="tip-body">Volume is always in cubic units (cm³, m³). Surface area is in square units (cm², m²). If you get a volume answer in cm² — you made an error somewhere. Always check that your answer has the right unit type.</div></div>
  </div>
</div>

