  <button class="q-tab" onclick="switchQ(1,this)">Question 2</button>
  <button class="q-tab" onclick="switchQ(2,this)">Question 3</button>
</div>

<div class="q-panel active" id="qp-0">
  <div class="math-layout">
    <div class="problem-panel">
      <div class="panel-label">Problem</div>
      <div class="problem-text">A cone has a radius of 6 cm and a height of 10 cm.</div>
      <div class="hint">V = ⅓πr²h. Don't forget the ⅓! Substitute r = 6 and h = 10.</div>
    </div>
    <div class="q-panel-inner">
      <div class="q-label">Question 1 · Cone Volume</div>
      <div class="q-text">What is the volume of the cone? (Leave in terms of π.)</div>
      <div class="opts" id="opts-0">
        <div class="opt" onclick="pick(0,this,'A')"><span class="opt-l">A</span>360π cm³</div>
        <div class="opt" onclick="pick(0,this,'B')"><span class="opt-l">B</span>120π cm³</div>
        <div class="opt" onclick="pick(0,this,'C')"><span class="opt-l">C</span>240π cm³</div>
        <div class="opt" onclick="pick(0,this,'D')"><span class="opt-l">D</span>180π cm³</div>
      </div>
      <div class="q-actions">
        <div class="feedback" id="fb-0-ok"><strong>Correct! 120π cm³</strong><div class="fb-work">V = ⅓πr²h = ⅓ × π × 36 × 10<br>= ⅓ × 360π = 120π cm³ ✓<br><br>Option A (360π) is the CYLINDER volume — missing the ⅓.<br>Option D (180π) uses ½ instead of ⅓.</div></div>
        <div class="feedback" id="fb-0-fail"><strong>Not quite.</strong> V = ⅓πr²h. The ⅓ is critical — don't forget it! ⅓ × π × 6² × 10.<div class="fb-work">⅓ × 360π = 120π cm³</div></div>
        <button class="btn-check" id="btn-0" onclick="check(0,'B')" disabled>Check answer</button>
      </div>
    </div>
  </div>
</div>

<div class="q-panel" id="qp-1">
  <div class="math-layout">
    <div class="problem-panel">
      <div class="panel-label">Problem</div>
      <div class="problem-text">A large sphere has radius 6 cm. A small sphere has radius 2 cm.</div>
      <div class="hint">Volume scales as the cube of the linear dimension. Scale factor = 6/2 = 3. Volume ratio = 3³ = 27. No need to compute each volume separately.</div>
    </div>
    <div class="q-panel-inner">
      <div class="q-label">Question 2 · Volume Scaling</div>
      <div class="q-text">How many times greater is the volume of the large sphere than the small sphere?</div>
      <div class="opts" id="opts-1">
        <div class="opt" onclick="pick(1,this,'A')"><span class="opt-l">A</span>3 times</div>
        <div class="opt" onclick="pick(1,this,'B')"><span class="opt-l">B</span>9 times</div>
        <div class="opt" onclick="pick(1,this,'C')"><span class="opt-l">C</span>27 times</div>
        <div class="opt" onclick="pick(1,this,'D')"><span class="opt-l">D</span>216 times</div>
      </div>
      <div class="q-actions">
        <div class="feedback" id="fb-1-ok"><strong>Correct! 27 times</strong><div class="fb-work">Linear scale factor k = 6/2 = 3<br>Volume ratio = k³ = 3³ = 27<br><br>Verify: V_large = (4/3)π(6)³ = 288π<br>V_small = (4/3)π(2)³ = (32/3)π<br>Ratio = 288π ÷ (32/3)π = 288 × 3/32 = 27 ✓</div></div>
        <div class="feedback" id="fb-1-fail"><strong>Not quite.</strong> Volume scales as the CUBE of the linear scale factor. Linear ratio = 6/2 = 3. Volume ratio = 3³.<div class="fb-work">3³ = 27 times larger</div></div>
        <button class="btn-check" id="btn-1" onclick="check(1,'C')" disabled>Check answer</button>
      </div>
    </div>
  </div>
</div>

<div class="q-panel" id="qp-2">
  <div class="math-layout">
    <div class="problem-panel">
      <div class="panel-label">Problem</div>
      <div class="problem-text">A rectangular aquarium is 80 cm long, 40 cm wide, and 50 cm tall. It is currently filled to 60% capacity. Water is added at a rate of 2,000 cm³ per minute.</div>
      <div class="hint">Total volume = 80×40×50 = 160,000 cm³. Current water = 60% × 160,000 = 96,000 cm³. Remaining = 40% × 160,000 = 64,000 cm³. Time = remaining ÷ rate.</div>
    </div>
    <div class="q-panel-inner">
      <div class="q-label">Question 3 · Volume Application</div>
      <div class="q-text">How many minutes will it take to fill the aquarium completely?</div>
      <div class="opts" id="opts-2">
        <div class="opt" onclick="pick(2,this,'A')"><span class="opt-l">A</span>32 minutes</div>
        <div class="opt" onclick="pick(2,this,'B')"><span class="opt-l">B</span>48 minutes</div>
        <div class="opt" onclick="pick(2,this,'C')"><span class="opt-l">C</span>80 minutes</div>
        <div class="opt" onclick="pick(2,this,'D')"><span class="opt-l">D</span>64 minutes</div>
      </div>
      <div class="q-actions">
        <div class="feedback" id="fb-2-ok"><strong>Correct! 32 minutes</strong><div class="fb-work">Total volume = 80×40×50 = 160,000 cm³<br>Already filled: 60% × 160,000 = 96,000 cm³<br>Remaining: 40% × 160,000 = 64,000 cm³<br>Time = 64,000 ÷ 2,000 = 32 minutes ✓</div></div>
        <div class="feedback" id="fb-2-fail"><strong>Not quite.</strong> Find total volume first (l×w×h). Then 40% remains to be filled. Divide remaining volume by the fill rate.<div class="fb-work">160,000 × 0.40 = 64,000 cm³ · 64,000 ÷ 2,000 = 32 min</div></div>
        <button class="btn-check" id="btn-2" onclick="check(2,'A')" disabled>Check answer</button>
      </div>
    </div>
  </div>
</div>

