<div class="tag">SAT Math · Module 4 · Lesson 4.10</div>
<div class="lesson-title">Coordinate Geometry</div>
<div class="lesson-sub">Master distance, midpoint, and partition formulas — and apply coordinate geometry to find areas, perimeters, and properties of shapes plotted in the xy-plane.</div>
<div class="dur-row"><span><b>12 min</b> read</span><span><b>3</b> practice questions</span><span><b>+20 pts</b> on completion</span></div>

<div class="card">
  <div class="sec-title">The core coordinate formulas</div>
  <div class="formula-box">
    <div class="formula">
      Distance: d = √[(x₂−x₁)² + (y₂−y₁)²]<br>
      Midpoint: M = ((x₁+x₂)/2, (y₁+y₂)/2)<br>
      Partition: P = (x₁ + m/(m+n)·(x₂−x₁), y₁ + m/(m+n)·(y₂−y₁))
    </div>
  </div>
  <table class="concept-table">
    <tr><th>Situation</th><th>Formula to use</th><th>Notes</th></tr>
    <tr><td>Length of a segment</td><td><em>distance formula</em></td><td>Same as Pythagorean theorem — the segment is the hypotenuse of a right triangle</td></tr>
    <tr><td>Center of a segment</td><td><em>midpoint formula</em></td><td>Average the x-coordinates and y-coordinates separately</td></tr>
    <tr><td>Point dividing segment in ratio m:n</td><td><em>partition formula</em></td><td>Moves m/(m+n) of the way from point 1 to point 2</td></tr>
    <tr><td>Area of polygon in coordinate plane</td><td><em>shoelace formula or decompose</em></td><td>Break into triangles or use ½|Σ(xᵢyᵢ₊₁ − xᵢ₊₁yᵢ)|</td></tr>
    <tr><td>Slope of a segment</td><td><em>m = (y₂−y₁)/(x₂−x₁)</em></td><td>Used to check parallel, perpendicular, or collinear points</td></tr>
  </table>
  <div class="example-box">
    <div class="example-label">Worked example — partition point</div>
    <div class="example-text">
      Point P divides segment AB in ratio 2:3, where A = (1, 2) and B = (6, 12).<br><br>
      <span class="fb-work">P_x = 1 + 2/(2+3) × (6−1) = 1 + (2/5)(5) = 1 + 2 = 3</span><br>
      <span class="fb-work">P_y = 2 + 2/(2+3) × (12−2) = 2 + (2/5)(10) = 2 + 4 = 6</span><br>
      P = (3, 6)
    </div>
  </div>
</div>

<div class="card">
  <div class="sec-title">SAT strategy tips</div>
  <div class="tips-grid">
    <div class="tip"><div class="tip-title">Distance = Pythagorean theorem</div><div class="tip-body">The distance formula is just a² + b² = c² in disguise: Δx and Δy are the two legs, the distance is the hypotenuse. If the numbers are clean, check if they're a Pythagorean triple before computing the square root.</div></div>
    <div class="tip"><div class="tip-title">Midpoint: average both coordinates</div><div class="tip-body">Average the x-values and average the y-values separately. If you know the midpoint and one endpoint, set up equations: midpoint = (x₁+x₂)/2 and solve for the unknown endpoint.</div></div>
    <div class="tip"><div class="tip-title">Partition: identify which endpoint you start from</div><div class="tip-body">In ratio m:n, you move m/(m+n) of the way from the first point to the second. Always identify which point is "first" from the problem statement — getting this wrong flips the answer.</div></div>
    <div class="tip"><div class="tip-title">Check collinearity with slope</div><div class="tip-body">Three points are collinear if any two pairs give the same slope. If slopes AB and BC are equal, then A, B, C are on the same line. Use this to verify answers in coordinate geometry problems.</div></div>
  </div>
</div>

