<div class="tag">SAT Math · Module 4 · Lesson 4.11</div>
<div class="lesson-title">Statistics & Data Analysis</div>
<div class="lesson-sub">Go deeper on statistics — sampling methods, margin of error, study design, and drawing valid conclusions from data — the critical reasoning layer the SAT adds on top of basic statistics.</div>
<div class="dur-row"><span><b>13 min</b> read</span><span><b>3</b> practice questions</span><span><b>+20 pts</b> on completion</span></div>

<div class="card">
  <div class="sec-title">Beyond the numbers — study design and inference</div>
  <div class="body-text">The SAT doesn't just ask you to calculate statistics. It asks whether conclusions drawn from a study are valid. This requires understanding how data was collected and what it can and cannot tell us.</div>
  <div class="concept-grid">
    <div class="concept-card">
      <div class="concept-title">Random sampling</div>
      <div class="concept-body">A random sample allows generalizations to the population it was drawn from. Non-random samples (convenience, voluntary) may be biased — results may not generalize.</div>
      <div class="concept-ex">Random survey of 500 voters → can generalize to all voters. Survey only online → biased toward internet users.</div>
    </div>
    <div class="concept-card">
      <div class="concept-title">Observational study vs. experiment</div>
      <div class="concept-body">Observational studies can show association but NOT causation. Only randomized controlled experiments can establish causation.</div>
      <div class="concept-ex">Observational: people who eat breakfast earn more. Cannot say breakfast causes higher earnings — confounding variables exist.</div>
    </div>
    <div class="concept-card">
      <div class="concept-title">Margin of error</div>
      <div class="concept-body">Survey results come with uncertainty: reported value ± margin of error. If two groups' intervals overlap, you cannot conclude they are different.</div>
      <div class="concept-ex">Group A: 52% ± 4% → (48%, 56%)<br>Group B: 49% ± 4% → (45%, 53%)<br>Intervals overlap → can't say A > B.</div>
    </div>
    <div class="concept-card">
      <div class="concept-title">Sample size and confidence</div>
      <div class="concept-body">Larger samples reduce margin of error and produce more reliable estimates. A study with n=50 is less reliable than n=5,000, all else being equal.</div>
    </div>
    <div class="concept-card">
      <div class="concept-title">Confounding variables</div>
      <div class="concept-body">A lurking variable that affects both the explanatory and response variables, creating a spurious association. The SAT asks you to identify confounding variables when evaluating study conclusions.</div>
    </div>
    <div class="concept-card">
      <div class="concept-title">Generalizing to population</div>
      <div class="concept-body">Only random samples allow generalization. The conclusion must match the scope of the sample — you can only generalize to the population from which the sample was drawn.</div>
    </div>
  </div>
</div>

<div class="card">
  <div class="sec-title">SAT strategy tips</div>
  <div class="tips-grid">
    <div class="tip"><div class="tip-title">Association ≠ causation (again)</div><div class="tip-body">Even in this lesson — any conclusion saying "X causes Y" from an observational study is wrong. The SAT will always have this as a trap answer. Only a randomized experiment can establish causation.</div></div>
    <div class="tip"><div class="tip-title">Scope of conclusion must match sample</div><div class="tip-body">If a study surveys students at one high school, conclusions can only apply to students at that school — not all students nationwide. "Overgeneralizing" is always a wrong answer.</div></div>
    <div class="tip"><div class="tip-title">Overlapping margin of error intervals</div><div class="tip-body">If two confidence intervals overlap, you cannot conclude one group is higher than the other. The SAT frequently tests this — look for "the data support the conclusion that Group A scored higher" when intervals overlap.</div></div>
    <div class="tip"><div class="tip-title">Random assignment eliminates confounding</div><div class="tip-body">In a randomized experiment, participants are randomly assigned to treatment or control. This balances confounding variables and allows causal conclusions — it's the key distinction between experiments and observational studies.</div></div>
  </div>
</div>

