<div class="q-tabs">
  <button class="q-tab active" onclick="switchQ(0,this)">Question 1</button>
  <button class="q-tab" onclick="switchQ(1,this)">Question 2</button>
  <button class="q-tab" onclick="switchQ(2,this)">Question 3</button>
</div>

<div class="q-panel active" id="qp-0">
  <div class="math-layout">
    <div class="problem-panel">
      <div class="panel-label">Problem</div>
      <div class="problem-text">Researchers randomly selected 800 adults from a city and found that 68% reported exercising at least three times per week. The margin of error was ±3.5%.</div>
      <div class="hint">Margin of error creates a confidence interval: 68% ± 3.5% = (64.5%, 71.5%). Conclusions that fall within this range are supported; conclusions outside are not supported.</div>
    </div>
    <div class="q-panel-inner">
      <div class="q-label">Question 1 · Margin of Error</div>
      <div class="q-text">Which conclusion is <strong>best supported</strong> by this data?</div>
      <div class="opts" id="opts-0">
        <div class="opt" onclick="pick(0,this,'A')"><span class="opt-l">A</span>Exactly 68% of all adults in the city exercise at least three times per week.</div>
        <div class="opt" onclick="pick(0,this,'B')"><span class="opt-l">B</span>It is plausible that between 64.5% and 71.5% of adults in the city exercise at least three times per week.</div>
        <div class="opt" onclick="pick(0,this,'C')"><span class="opt-l">C</span>More than 75% of adults in the city exercise at least three times per week.</div>
        <div class="opt" onclick="pick(0,this,'D')"><span class="opt-l">D</span>These results apply to all adults in the country.</div>
      </div>
      <div class="q-actions">
        <div class="feedback" id="fb-0-ok"><strong>Correct!</strong> Option B correctly states the confidence interval: 68% ± 3.5% = 64.5% to 71.5%. This is the appropriate conclusion from a survey with a margin of error. Option A claims exactness — surveys never give exact values. Option C (75%) is outside the confidence interval. Option D overgeneralizes — the sample was from one city, not the country.</div>
        <div class="feedback" id="fb-0-fail"><strong>Not quite.</strong> The margin of error means the true value is likely 68% ± 3.5% = between 64.5% and 71.5%. Which conclusion stays within this range and uses appropriately uncertain language?</div>
        <button class="btn-check" id="btn-0" onclick="check(0,'B')" disabled>Check answer</button>
      </div>
    </div>
  </div>
</div>

<div class="q-panel" id="qp-1">
  <div class="math-layout">
    <div class="problem-panel">
      <div class="panel-label">Problem</div>
      <div class="problem-text">A school randomly assigned 150 students to either a new study skills program or a control group. After 6 weeks, students in the program scored an average of 12 points higher on tests than the control group.</div>
      <div class="hint">Key question: was this an observational study or a randomized experiment? Random assignment is the key phrase. Does random assignment allow causal conclusions?</div>
    </div>
    <div class="q-panel-inner">
      <div class="q-label">Question 2 · Study Design</div>
      <div class="q-text">Which conclusion is <strong>most justified</strong> by this study?</div>
      <div class="opts" id="opts-1">
        <div class="opt" onclick="pick(1,this,'A')"><span class="opt-l">A</span>Students who study more naturally score higher, which explains the difference.</div>
        <div class="opt" onclick="pick(1,this,'B')"><span class="opt-l">B</span>The study skills program caused an improvement in test scores among the students in this study.</div>
        <div class="opt" onclick="pick(1,this,'C')"><span class="opt-l">C</span>All students in the country would improve by 12 points if given this program.</div>
        <div class="opt" onclick="pick(1,this,'D')"><span class="opt-l">D</span>There is an association between the program and test scores, but causation cannot be determined.</div>
      </div>
      <div class="q-actions">
        <div class="feedback" id="fb-1-ok"><strong>Correct!</strong> Because students were randomly assigned (not self-selected), this is a randomized controlled experiment — the gold standard for causal inference. Option B correctly identifies a causal conclusion limited to the study participants. Option C overgeneralizes. Option D is wrong — random assignment DOES allow causal conclusions. Option A invents an explanation not in the study.</div>
        <div class="feedback" id="fb-1-fail"><strong>Not quite.</strong> The key detail is "randomly assigned." Random assignment creates comparable groups and eliminates confounding — it's what makes causal conclusions possible in experiments. What scope is appropriate for this conclusion?</div>
        <button class="btn-check" id="btn-1" onclick="check(1,'B')" disabled>Check answer</button>
      </div>
    </div>
  </div>
</div>

<div class="q-panel" id="qp-2">
  <div class="math-layout">
    <div class="problem-panel">
      <div class="panel-label">Problem</div>
      <div class="problem-text">A survey of 200 randomly selected customers at a coffee shop found that 74% preferred oat milk over regular milk. The margin of error was ±6%.</div>
      <div class="problem-text" style="margin-top:.5rem;">A separate survey of 200 randomly selected customers at the same coffee shop the following week found that 68% preferred oat milk. The margin of error was also ±6%.</div>
      <div class="hint">Week 1 interval: 74% ± 6% = (68%, 80%). Week 2 interval: 68% ± 6% = (62%, 74%). Do these intervals overlap?</div>
    </div>
    <div class="q-panel-inner">
      <div class="q-label">Question 3 · Overlapping Intervals</div>
      <div class="q-text">Which statement is <strong>best supported</strong> by the two surveys?</div>
      <div class="opts" id="opts-2">
        <div class="opt" onclick="pick(2,this,'A')"><span class="opt-l">A</span>Oat milk preference significantly declined between the two weeks.</div>
        <div class="opt" onclick="pick(2,this,'B')"><span class="opt-l">B</span>The difference in results between the two weeks is statistically meaningful.</div>
        <div class="opt" onclick="pick(2,this,'C')"><span class="opt-l">C</span>The two surveys are consistent — the observed difference is within the range of sampling variability.</div>
        <div class="opt" onclick="pick(2,this,'D')"><span class="opt-l">D</span>Week 1 preference was definitely higher than Week 2.</div>
      </div>
      <div class="q-actions">
        <div class="feedback" id="fb-2-ok"><strong>Correct!</strong><div class="fb-work">Week 1 interval: 68% to 80%<br>Week 2 interval: 62% to 74%<br>Overlap region: 68% to 74%<br><br>The intervals overlap significantly → the difference (74% vs 68%) is within sampling variability. We cannot conclude there was a real change. Options A, B, and D all claim the difference is meaningful — but with overlapping intervals, this cannot be concluded.</div></div>
        <div class="feedback" id="fb-2-fail"><strong>Not quite.</strong> Calculate each confidence interval: Week 1 = 68%–80%, Week 2 = 62%–74%. Do they overlap? If yes, the difference is within sampling variability — we cannot conclude a real change occurred.<div class="fb-work">Overlap: 68%–74% → consistent, not a significant change</div></div>
        <button class="btn-check" id="btn-2" onclick="check(2,'C')" disabled>Check answer</button>
      </div>
    </div>
  </div>
</div>

