<div class="lesson-title">Complex Numbers</div>
<div class="lesson-sub">Master operations with complex numbers — addition, subtraction, multiplication, and division — and the cyclic powers of i that the SAT uses in every complex number problem.</div>
<div class="dur-row"><span><b>11 min</b> read</span><span><b>3</b> practice questions</span><span><b>+20 pts</b> on completion</span></div>

<div class="card">
  <div class="sec-title">What is i and how do powers cycle?</div>
  <div class="body-text">The imaginary unit <strong>i</strong> is defined as √(−1), so i² = −1. Powers of i cycle with period 4 — this is the most important pattern to memorize.</div>
  <div class="powers-grid">
    <div class="pow-card"><div class="pow-eq">i¹</div><div class="pow-result">= i</div></div>
    <div class="pow-card"><div class="pow-eq">i²</div><div class="pow-result">= −1</div></div>
    <div class="pow-card"><div class="pow-eq">i³</div><div class="pow-result">= −i</div></div>
    <div class="pow-card"><div class="pow-eq">i⁴</div><div class="pow-result">= 1</div></div>
    <div class="pow-card"><div class="pow-eq">i⁵</div><div class="pow-result">= i (repeats)</div></div>
    <div class="pow-card"><div class="pow-eq">i⁶</div><div class="pow-result">= −1</div></div>
    <div class="pow-card"><div class="pow-eq">i⁷</div><div class="pow-result">= −i</div></div>
    <div class="pow-card"><div class="pow-eq">i⁸</div><div class="pow-result">= 1</div></div>
  </div>
  <div class="formula-box" style="margin-top:1rem;">
    <div class="formula">To find iⁿ: divide n by 4, use the remainder.<br>Remainder 0 → 1 · Remainder 1 → i · Remainder 2 → −1 · Remainder 3 → −i</div>
  </div>
</div>

<div class="card">
  <div class="sec-title">Operations with complex numbers</div>
  <div class="body-text">A complex number has the form <strong>a + bi</strong> where a is the real part and b is the imaginary part.</div>
  <div class="ops-grid">
    <div class="op-card">
      <div class="op-title">Adding & Subtracting</div>
      <div class="op-rule">Combine real parts and imaginary parts separately.</div>
      <div class="op-ex">(3+2i)+(5−4i) = 8−2i<br>(7+i)−(3−6i) = 4+7i</div>
    </div>
    <div class="op-card">
      <div class="op-title">Multiplying — use FOIL then replace i²=−1</div>
      <div class="op-rule">Distribute (FOIL), then substitute i² = −1 to simplify.</div>
      <div class="op-ex">(2+3i)(1−4i)<br>= 2−8i+3i−12i²<br>= 2−5i−12(−1)<br>= 14−5i</div>
    </div>
    <div class="op-card">
      <div class="op-title">Complex conjugate</div>
      <div class="op-rule">The conjugate of a+bi is a−bi. Their product is always real: (a+bi)(a−bi) = a²+b².</div>
      <div class="op-ex">Conjugate of 3+4i is 3−4i<br>(3+4i)(3−4i) = 9+16 = 25</div>
    </div>
    <div class="op-card">
      <div class="op-title">Dividing — multiply by conjugate</div>
      <div class="op-rule">Multiply numerator and denominator by the conjugate of the denominator to eliminate i from the denominator.</div>
      <div class="op-ex">(1+2i)/(3+i)<br>= (1+2i)(3−i)/[(3+i)(3−i)]<br>= (3−i+6i−2i²)/(9+1)<br>= (5+5i)/10 = ½+½i</div>
    </div>
  </div>
  <div class="example-box">
    <div class="example-label">Worked example — finding iⁿ</div>
    <div class="example-text">
      What is i⁴⁷?<br><br>
      <span class="fb-work">Divide: 47 ÷ 4 = 11 remainder 3</span><br>
      <span class="fb-work">Remainder 3 → i³ = −i</span><br>
      <span class="fb-work">i⁴⁷ = −i</span>
    </div>
  </div>
</div>

<div class="card">
  <div class="sec-title">SAT strategy tips</div>
  <div class="tips-grid">
    <div class="tip"><div class="tip-title">Cycle trick: divide exponent by 4, use remainder</div><div class="tip-body">For any iⁿ, divide n by 4 and use the remainder: 0→1, 1→i, 2→−1, 3→−i. This handles any power instantly. i¹⁰⁰ → 100÷4=25 r0 → i¹⁰⁰ = 1.</div></div>
    <div class="tip"><div class="tip-title">Multiply by conjugate to divide</div><div class="tip-body">To simplify a fraction with i in the denominator, always multiply top and bottom by the conjugate. This clears the imaginary part from the denominator and leaves a real number there.</div></div>
    <div class="tip"><div class="tip-title">i² = −1, always</div><div class="tip-body">Every time i² appears (from FOIL or anywhere else), replace it with −1 immediately. This is the single most critical step in complex number arithmetic — missing it is the most common error.</div></div>
    <div class="tip"><div class="tip-title">Real and imaginary parts stay separate</div><div class="tip-body">When adding complex numbers, keep real and imaginary terms separate. (3+2i) + (5+4i) = 8+6i — never combine a real term with an imaginary term into a single number.</div></div>
  </div>
</div>

<div class="sec-title" style="margin-bottom:.75rem">Practice questions</div>
<div class="q-tabs">
