<div class="lesson-title">Polynomial & Rational Functions</div>
<div class="lesson-sub">Master end behavior, zeros, and graph features of polynomial functions — and vertical/horizontal asymptotes, holes, and domain restrictions of rational functions.</div>
<div class="dur-row"><span><b>13 min</b> read</span><span><b>3</b> practice questions</span><span><b>+20 pts</b> on completion</span></div>

<div class="card">
  <div class="sec-title">Polynomial function features</div>
  <table class="concept-table">
    <tr><th>Feature</th><th>How to find it</th><th>Example</th></tr>
    <tr><td>Zeros / x-intercepts</td><td>Set f(x) = 0, solve. Each factor (x−r) gives a root at x = r.</td><td><em>f(x)=(x−2)(x+3)(x−1)</em> has zeros at x=2,−3,1</td></tr>
    <tr><td>y-intercept</td><td>Substitute x = 0.</td><td><em>f(0) = (0−2)(0+3)(0−1) = (−2)(3)(−1) = 6</em></td></tr>
    <tr><td>End behavior (even degree)</td><td>Both ends go same direction. a>0: both up. a&lt;0: both down.</td><td><em>f(x)=2x⁴−...</em>: as x→±∞, f→+∞</td></tr>
    <tr><td>End behavior (odd degree)</td><td>Ends go opposite directions. a>0: left down, right up.</td><td><em>f(x)=x³+...</em>: left down, right up</td></tr>
    <tr><td>Multiplicity of a root</td><td>If (x−r)² appears → root touches axis but doesn't cross. (x−r)¹ → crosses axis.</td><td><em>f(x)=(x−2)²(x+1)</em>: touches at x=2, crosses at x=−1</td></tr>
  </table>
</div>

<div class="card">
  <div class="sec-title">Rational function features</div>
  <div class="body-text">A rational function is a fraction of two polynomials: f(x) = p(x)/q(x). Its key features come from the numerator (zeros) and denominator (vertical asymptotes or holes).</div>
  <table class="concept-table">
    <tr><th>Feature</th><th>How to find it</th></tr>
    <tr><td>Vertical asymptote</td><td>Set denominator = 0, check that the numerator is NOT also 0 at that x. If so, there's a vertical asymptote at x = that value.</td></tr>
    <tr><td>Hole (removable discontinuity)</td><td>If both numerator AND denominator = 0 at the same x, factor and cancel — that x is a hole, not an asymptote.</td></tr>
    <tr><td>Horizontal asymptote</td><td>Compare degrees. If deg(num) &lt; deg(den): y = 0. If equal: y = leading coeff ratio. If deg(num) &gt; deg(den): no horizontal asymptote.</td></tr>
    <tr><td>x-intercepts</td><td>Set numerator = 0 (after cancelling holes). The remaining uncancelled zeros give x-intercepts.</td></tr>
  </table>
  <div class="example-box">
    <div class="example-label">Worked example</div>
    <div class="example-text">
      For f(x) = (x²−4) / (x²−x−6), find all features.<br><br>
      <span class="fb-work">Factor: (x+2)(x−2) / (x−3)(x+2)</span><br>
      <span class="fb-work">Cancel (x+2): = (x−2)/(x−3) with a hole at x = −2</span><br>
      <span class="fb-work">Vertical asymptote: x = 3 (denominator = 0, not cancelled)</span><br>
      <span class="fb-work">Horizontal asymptote: y = 1 (equal degree, ratio of leading coefficients)</span><br>
      <span class="fb-work">x-intercept: x = 2 (numerator = 0 after cancellation)</span>
    </div>
  </div>
</div>

<div class="card">
  <div class="sec-title">SAT strategy tips</div>
  <div class="tips-grid">
    <div class="tip"><div class="tip-title">End behavior: focus on leading term only</div><div class="tip-body">For large |x|, only the leading term matters. f(x) = −3x⁵ + ... behaves like −3x⁵ as x→±∞. Negative odd degree → left up, right down.</div></div>
    <div class="tip"><div class="tip-title">Factor before identifying asymptotes</div><div class="tip-body">Always factor numerator and denominator completely before labeling asymptotes or holes. If the same factor cancels, it's a hole. If it stays in the denominator, it's a vertical asymptote.</div></div>
    <div class="tip"><div class="tip-title">Horizontal asymptote: compare degrees</div><div class="tip-body">deg(num) &lt; deg(den) → y = 0. Same degree → y = ratio of leading coefficients. deg(num) &gt; deg(den) → no horizontal asymptote (oblique or none). Memorize these three cases.</div></div>
    <div class="tip"><div class="tip-title">Multiplicity affects graph behavior at roots</div><div class="tip-body">Even multiplicity (power 2, 4, ...) → graph touches and bounces off the x-axis. Odd multiplicity (power 1, 3, ...) → graph crosses through the x-axis. The SAT uses this to test graph identification questions.</div></div>
  </div>
</div>

<div class="sec-title" style="margin-bottom:.75rem">Practice questions</div>
<div class="q-tabs">
  <button class="q-tab active" onclick="switchQ(0,this)">Question 1</button>
  <button class="q-tab" onclick="switchQ(1,this)">Question 2</button>
  <button class="q-tab" onclick="switchQ(2,this)">Question 3</button>
</div>

<div class="q-panel active" id="qp-0">
  <div class="math-layout">
    <div class="problem-panel">
      <div class="panel-label">Problem</div>
      <div class="problem-text">The polynomial function:</div>
      <span class="math-eq">f(x) = −2x³ + 5x² − x + 3</span>
      <div class="hint">End behavior is determined by the leading term: −2x³. As x→+∞, −2x³→−∞. As x→−∞, −2x³→+∞. Negative odd degree → left up, right down.</div>
    </div>
    <div class="q-panel-inner">
      <div class="q-label">Question 1 · End Behavior</div>
      <div class="q-text">Which describes the <strong>end behavior</strong> of f(x)?</div>
      <div class="opts" id="opts-0">
        <div class="opt" onclick="pick(0,this,'A')"><span class="opt-l">A</span>As x→+∞, f→+∞ and as x→−∞, f→−∞</div>
        <div class="opt" onclick="pick(0,this,'B')"><span class="opt-l">B</span>As x→+∞, f→−∞ and as x→−∞, f→+∞</div>
        <div class="opt" onclick="pick(0,this,'C')"><span class="opt-l">C</span>As x→±∞, f→+∞</div>
        <div class="opt" onclick="pick(0,this,'D')"><span class="opt-l">D</span>As x→±∞, f→−∞</div>
      </div>
      <div class="q-actions">
        <div class="feedback" id="fb-0-ok"><strong>Correct!</strong> Leading term is −2x³ — negative coefficient, odd degree. Odd degree → ends in opposite directions. Negative leading coefficient → right goes down, left goes up. So: right → −∞, left → +∞. Options C and D describe even-degree behavior (both ends same direction).</div>
        <div class="feedback" id="fb-0-fail"><strong>Not quite.</strong> Focus on the leading term: −2x³. Odd degree → ends go opposite directions. Negative coefficient → flips the standard odd behavior (right goes DOWN, left goes UP).<div class="fb-work">x→+∞: −2x³→−∞ · x→−∞: −2x³→+∞</div></div>
        <button class="btn-check" id="btn-0" onclick="check(0,'B')" disabled>Check answer</button>
      </div>
    </div>
  </div>
</div>

<div class="q-panel" id="qp-1">
  <div class="math-layout">
    <div class="problem-panel">
      <div class="panel-label">Problem</div>
      <div class="problem-text">The rational function:</div>
      <span class="math-eq">f(x) = (x² − 9) / (x² − x − 6)</span>
      <div class="hint">Factor both: numerator = (x+3)(x−3). Denominator = (x−3)(x+2). Cancel the common factor (x−3) → hole at x=3. The remaining denominator factor (x+2) gives a vertical asymptote at x=−2.</div>
    </div>
    <div class="q-panel-inner">
      <div class="q-label">Question 2 · Holes vs. Asymptotes</div>
      <div class="q-text">This function has a <strong>hole</strong> at x = ? and a <strong>vertical asymptote</strong> at x = ?</div>
      <div class="opts" id="opts-1">
        <div class="opt" onclick="pick(1,this,'A')"><span class="opt-l">A</span>Hole at x = −2; vertical asymptote at x = 3</div>
        <div class="opt" onclick="pick(1,this,'B')"><span class="opt-l">B</span>Hole at x = 3; vertical asymptote at x = −2</div>
        <div class="opt" onclick="pick(1,this,'C')"><span class="opt-l">C</span>Vertical asymptotes at both x = 3 and x = −2</div>
        <div class="opt" onclick="pick(1,this,'D')"><span class="opt-l">D</span>Holes at both x = 3 and x = −2</div>
      </div>
      <div class="q-actions">
        <div class="feedback" id="fb-1-ok"><strong>Correct! Hole at x = 3; asymptote at x = −2</strong><div class="fb-work">Numerator: (x+3)(x−3)<br>Denominator: (x−3)(x+2)<br>Cancel (x−3): hole at x = 3<br>Remaining denominator: (x+2) = 0 → vertical asymptote at x = −2 ✓</div></div>
        <div class="feedback" id="fb-1-fail"><strong>Not quite.</strong> Factor both polynomials. If a factor cancels from both top and bottom, that x gives a HOLE. If a factor stays only in the denominator, it gives a VERTICAL ASYMPTOTE.<div class="fb-work">Cancel (x−3) → hole at 3. (x+2) stays → asymptote at −2.</div></div>
        <button class="btn-check" id="btn-1" onclick="check(1,'B')" disabled>Check answer</button>
      </div>
    </div>
  </div>
</div>

<div class="q-panel" id="qp-2">
  <div class="math-layout">
    <div class="problem-panel">
      <div class="panel-label">Problem</div>
      <div class="problem-text">A polynomial function f has roots at x = −1 (multiplicity 2) and x = 4 (multiplicity 1), and f(0) = −8.</div>
      <div class="hint">Factored form: f(x) = a(x+1)²(x−4). Use f(0)=−8 to find a: −8 = a(1)²(−4) = −4a → a = 2. The even multiplicity at x=−1 means the graph touches but doesn't cross there.</div>
    </div>
    <div class="q-panel-inner">
      <div class="q-label">Question 3 · Polynomial from Roots</div>
      <div class="q-text">Which equation represents f(x)?</div>
      <div class="opts" id="opts-2">
        <div class="opt" onclick="pick(2,this,'A')"><span class="opt-l">A</span>f(x) = (x+1)²(x−4)</div>
        <div class="opt" onclick="pick(2,this,'B')"><span class="opt-l">B</span>f(x) = 2(x+1)²(x−4)</div>
        <div class="opt" onclick="pick(2,this,'C')"><span class="opt-l">C</span>f(x) = 2(x−1)²(x+4)</div>
        <div class="opt" onclick="pick(2,this,'D')"><span class="opt-l">D</span>f(x) = −2(x+1)²(x−4)</div>
      </div>
      <div class="q-actions">
