<div class="lesson-title">Linear & Exponential Models in Context</div>
<div class="lesson-sub">Master the art of choosing between linear and exponential models from data, graphs, and word descriptions — and practice writing, interpreting, and comparing models in complex real-world contexts.</div>
<div class="dur-row"><span><b>13 min</b> read</span><span><b>3</b> practice questions</span><span><b>+20 pts</b> on completion</span></div>

<div class="card">
  <div class="sec-title">Choosing the right model</div>
  <div class="compare-grid">
    <div class="cmp-card" style="background:#f9fafb;">
      <div class="cmp-title">Linear model — constant difference</div>
      <div class="cmp-body">Use when equal changes in x produce equal changes in y. The rate of change is constant. Graph is a straight line.</div>
      <div class="cmp-ex">Table test: Δy is constant for equal Δx<br>Words: "adds $50 per month," "increases by 200 per year"<br>f(x) = mx + b</div>
    </div>
    <div class="cmp-card" style="background:#FEF3C7;">
      <div class="cmp-title">Exponential model — constant ratio</div>
      <div class="cmp-body">Use when equal changes in x produce equal ratios of y. The percent change is constant. Graph curves.</div>
      <div class="cmp-ex">Table test: y₂/y₁ is constant for equal Δx<br>Words: "grows by 8% annually," "doubles every 5 years"<br>f(x) = a·bˣ</div>
    </div>
  </div>
  <div class="select-grid">
    <div class="sel-card">
      <div class="sel-title">From a table — check differences vs. ratios</div>
      <div class="sel-body">If consecutive y-values have constant differences → linear. If they have constant ratios → exponential. Compute both and see which is consistent.</div>
    </div>
    <div class="sel-card">
      <div class="sel-title">From a word problem — key phrases</div>
      <div class="sel-body">"By X per period" → linear (constant amount). "By X% per period" → exponential (constant rate). "X times as large" → exponential.</div>
    </div>
    <div class="sel-card">
      <div class="sel-title">When linear eventually overtakes exponential</div>
      <div class="sel-body">For small values, a linear model can be larger. But exponential always wins for large enough x because it grows without bound faster than any linear function.</div>
    </div>
    <div class="sel-card">
      <div class="sel-title">Fitting a model to two points</div>
      <div class="sel-body">For linear: use slope formula + y-intercept. For exponential: set up f(x) = a·bˣ, use two points to create two equations, solve for a and b.</div>
    </div>
  </div>
  <div class="example-box">
    <div class="example-label">Worked example — fitting an exponential model</div>
    <div class="example-text">
      A population was 2,000 in year 0 and 2,500 in year 4. Assuming exponential growth, find the model.<br><br>
      <span class="fb-work">f(x) = a·bˣ · f(0) = a = 2,000</span><br>
      <span class="fb-work">f(4) = 2,000·b⁴ = 2,500</span><br>
      <span class="fb-work">b⁴ = 1.25 → b = 1.25^(1/4) ≈ 1.0574</span><br>
      <span class="fb-work">f(x) = 2,000 · (1.0574)ˣ → about 5.74% annual growth</span>
    </div>
  </div>
</div>

<div class="card">
  <div class="sec-title">SAT strategy tips</div>
  <div class="tips-grid">
    <div class="tip"><div class="tip-title">Table: check differences first, then ratios</div><div class="tip-body">For any table in the calculator section, compute consecutive differences (Δy). If constant → linear. If not constant, compute consecutive ratios (y₂/y₁). If constant → exponential. This two-step check handles every model identification question.</div></div>
    <div class="tip"><div class="tip-title">"Percent change" always signals exponential</div><div class="tip-body">Any phrase containing "percent," "rate," or "times as large" describes exponential behavior. A fixed dollar or unit amount signals linear. This vocabulary distinction appears in almost every "identify the model" question.</div></div>
    <div class="tip"><div class="tip-title">The y-intercept is always f(0) = a</div><div class="tip-body">In both linear (f(0) = b) and exponential (f(0) = a), the y-intercept is the value when x = 0. For exponential, this is the starting value a. For linear, it's the fixed offset b. The SAT always asks about f(0).</div></div>
    <div class="tip"><div class="tip-title">Which model fits better: compare residuals</div><div class="tip-body">If the SAT gives a scatterplot and asks which model fits better, check whether the residuals (vertical distances from points to curve) are smaller for the linear or exponential fit. The better model has smaller, more random residuals.</div></div>
  </div>
</div>

