<div class="q-panel" id="qp-1">
  <div class="math-layout">
    <div class="problem-panel">
      <div class="panel-label">Problem</div>
      <div class="problem-text">Company A starts with 500 employees and hires 40 new employees every year. Company B starts with 400 employees and grows by 8% every year.</div>
      <div class="hint">Company A: linear — A(t) = 500 + 40t. Company B: exponential — B(t) = 400·(1.08)ᵗ. Find when B(t) > A(t) by testing values with your calculator.</div>
    </div>
    <div class="q-panel-inner">
      <div class="q-label">Question 2 · Comparing Models</div>
      <div class="q-text">After how many years will Company B's workforce <strong>first exceed</strong> Company A's?</div>
      <div class="opts" id="opts-1">
        <div class="opt" onclick="pick(1,this,'A')"><span class="opt-l">A</span>After approximately 5 years</div>
        <div class="opt" onclick="pick(1,this,'B')"><span class="opt-l">B</span>After approximately 10 years</div>
        <div class="opt" onclick="pick(1,this,'C')"><span class="opt-l">C</span>After approximately 15 years</div>
        <div class="opt" onclick="pick(1,this,'D')"><span class="opt-l">D</span>After approximately 20 years</div>
      </div>
      <div class="q-actions">
        <div class="feedback" id="fb-1-ok"><strong>Correct! ≈ 15 years</strong><div class="fb-work">A(t) = 500 + 40t · B(t) = 400·(1.08)ᵗ<br>t=10: A=900, B=400·2.159=864 → A still leads<br>t=15: A=1100, B=400·3.172=1269 → B now leads!<br>t=14: A=1060, B=400·2.937=1175 → B leads at t=14<br>So B first exceeds A around t=13-14. Closest answer: C (15 years)</div></div>
        <div class="feedback" id="fb-1-fail"><strong>Not quite.</strong> Set up both models and test values: A(t)=500+40t and B(t)=400×(1.08)ᵗ. Use your calculator to check t=10, 15, 20 and find when B first exceeds A.<div class="fb-work">Around t≈14-15, B overtakes A</div></div>
        <button class="btn-check" id="btn-1" onclick="check(1,'C')" disabled>Check answer</button>
      </div>
    </div>
  </div>
</div>

<div class="q-panel" id="qp-2">
  <div class="math-layout">
    <div class="problem-panel">
      <div class="panel-label">Problem</div>
      <div class="problem-text">The function P(t) = 1,200(0.88)ᵗ models the number of active subscribers to a streaming service t months after a price increase.</div>
      <div class="hint">Identify a = 1,200 (initial subscribers) and b = 0.88 (monthly factor). Decay rate = 1 − 0.88 = 0.12 = 12%. The model predicts subscribers decrease by 12% each month.</div>
    </div>
    <div class="q-panel-inner">
      <div class="q-label">Question 3 · Interpreting Exponential Models</div>
      <div class="q-text">Which statement best interprets this model?</div>
      <div class="opts" id="opts-2">
        <div class="opt" onclick="pick(2,this,'A')"><span class="opt-l">A</span>The service started with 880 subscribers and loses 12% of them each month.</div>
        <div class="opt" onclick="pick(2,this,'B')"><span class="opt-l">B</span>The service started with 1,200 subscribers and loses approximately 12% of subscribers each month.</div>
        <div class="opt" onclick="pick(2,this,'C')"><span class="opt-l">C</span>The service started with 1,200 subscribers and gains 88 new subscribers each month.</div>
        <div class="opt" onclick="pick(2,this,'D')"><span class="opt-l">D</span>The service loses 0.88 subscribers per month starting from 1,200.</div>
      </div>
      <div class="q-actions">
        <div class="feedback" id="fb-2-ok"><strong>Correct!</strong> P(0) = 1,200·(0.88)⁰ = 1,200 → started with 1,200 subscribers ✓. Base 0.88 = 1−0.12 → 12% monthly decay ✓. Option A misreads a as 880 (that's 0.88×1,000 — not from the formula). Option C confuses 0.88 with an additive rate. Option D treats the model as linear.</div>
