<div class="lesson-title">Two-Variable Data</div>
<div class="lesson-sub">Master scatterplots, lines and curves of best fit, residuals, and two-way frequency tables at a deeper level — the data reasoning the SAT tests in its most sophisticated questions.</div>
<div class="dur-row"><span><b>13 min</b> read</span><span><b>3</b> practice questions</span><span><b>+20 pts</b> on completion</span></div>

<div class="card">
  <div class="sec-title">Scatterplot analysis — the full toolkit</div>
  <div class="concept-grid">
    <div class="c-card">
      <div class="c-title">Linear vs. nonlinear fit</div>
      <div class="c-body">If residuals form a curved pattern (all positive then all negative), a linear model is a poor fit — try a quadratic or exponential curve instead.</div>
      <div class="c-ex">Random residuals around zero → good linear fit<br>U-shaped residuals → try quadratic fit</div>
    </div>
    <div class="c-card">
      <div class="c-title">Residual plots</div>
      <div class="c-body">A residual plot shows (x, actual − predicted) for each point. A good model has residuals randomly scattered around y = 0 with no visible pattern.</div>
    </div>
    <div class="c-card">
      <div class="c-title">Outliers and influential points</div>
      <div class="c-body">An outlier far from the trend can shift the line of best fit significantly. Always check whether removing an outlier changes the slope or intercept substantially.</div>
    </div>
    <div class="c-card">
      <div class="c-title">Two-way tables — relative frequency</div>
      <div class="c-body">Relative frequency = cell count / total. Row relative frequency uses the row total as denominator. Column relative frequency uses the column total.</div>
      <div class="c-ex">Cell count 40, row total 100 → row relative freq = 40%<br>Cell count 40, grand total 200 → overall freq = 20%</div>
    </div>
    <div class="c-card">
      <div class="c-title">Correlation coefficient r</div>
      <div class="c-body">r ranges from −1 to +1. |r| close to 1 → strong association. |r| close to 0 → weak association. Sign indicates direction. r = 0 does NOT mean no relationship — only no linear relationship.</div>
    </div>
    <div class="c-card">
      <div class="c-title">Association vs. independence (two-way tables)</div>
      <div class="c-body">Two variables are independent if the conditional distribution of one is the same across all categories of the other. If distributions differ, the variables are associated.</div>
    </div>
  </div>
  <div class="example-box">
    <div class="example-label">Two-way table — checking for association</div>
    <div class="example-text">
      In a survey of 200 students, the table shows music preference by grade:<br><br>
      <table class="two-way" style="margin:.5rem 0;">
        <tr><th></th><th>Pop</th><th>Rock</th><th>Total</th></tr>
        <tr><td><strong>Grade 10</strong></td><td>60</td><td>40</td><td class="total">100</td></tr>
        <tr><td><strong>Grade 11</strong></td><td>60</td><td>40</td><td class="total">100</td></tr>
        <tr><td class="total">Total</td><td class="total">120</td><td class="total">80</td><td class="total">200</td></tr>
      </table>
      <span class="fb-work">Grade 10: P(Pop) = 60/100 = 60%</span><br>
      <span class="fb-work">Grade 11: P(Pop) = 60/100 = 60%</span><br>
      Identical conditional distributions → grade and music preference are <strong>independent</strong>.
    </div>
  </div>
</div>

<div class="card">
  <div class="sec-title">SAT strategy tips</div>
  <div class="tips-grid">
    <div class="tip"><div class="tip-title">Residual = actual − predicted (always this order)</div><div class="tip-body">Residual is always actual minus predicted, never the reverse. A positive residual means the actual value is above the line of best fit. A negative residual means it's below. The SAT tests this sign convention.</div></div>
    <div class="tip"><div class="tip-title">Check for association in two-way tables by comparing conditional distributions</div><div class="tip-body">If the row percentages are the same across all rows, the two variables are independent. If they differ, there is an association. Don't rely on the counts alone — always convert to percentages within each row or column.</div></div>
    <div class="tip"><div class="tip-title">r close to ±1 doesn't mean causation</div><div class="tip-body">A high correlation coefficient (|r| near 1) means strong linear association — not causation. This is the same correlation vs. causation principle from Lesson 4.11, applied to numerical context.</div></div>
    <div class="tip"><div class="tip-title">Nonlinear fit: look at the residual pattern</div><div class="tip-body">If a residual plot shows a curved or systematic pattern rather than random scatter, the linear model is inadequate. The SAT will show you two residual plots and ask which model is better — choose the one with random scatter around zero.</div></div>
  </div>
</div>

<div class="sec-title" style="margin-bottom:.75rem">Practice questions</div>
