      <div class="panel-label">Scatterplot context</div>
      <div class="problem-text">A line of best fit for a data set has equation y = 3x + 8. One data point is (5, 28).</div>
      <div class="hint">Residual = actual − predicted. Predicted at x=5: y = 3(5)+8 = 23. Actual = 28. Residual = 28−23 = 5. Positive means the point is above the line.</div>
    </div>
    <div class="q-panel-inner">
      <div class="q-label">Question 1 · Residuals</div>
      <div class="q-text">What is the residual for the point (5, 28) and what does it mean?</div>
      <div class="opts" id="opts-0">
        <div class="opt" onclick="pick(0,this,'A')"><span class="opt-l">A</span>Residual = −5; the point is below the line of best fit.</div>
        <div class="opt" onclick="pick(0,this,'B')"><span class="opt-l">B</span>Residual = 5; the point is above the line of best fit.</div>
        <div class="opt" onclick="pick(0,this,'C')"><span class="opt-l">C</span>Residual = 5; the point is below the line of best fit.</div>
        <div class="opt" onclick="pick(0,this,'D')"><span class="opt-l">D</span>Residual = 23; the predicted value at x = 5.</div>
      </div>
      <div class="q-actions">
        <div class="feedback" id="fb-0-ok"><strong>Correct!</strong><div class="fb-work">Predicted: y = 3(5)+8 = 23<br>Residual = actual − predicted = 28 − 23 = 5<br>Positive residual → point is ABOVE the line ✓</div></div>
        <div class="feedback" id="fb-0-fail"><strong>Not quite.</strong> Residual = actual − predicted. First find predicted: y = 3(5)+8 = 23. Then 28 − 23 = 5. Positive → above the line.<div class="fb-work">Residual = 28−23 = +5 → above the line</div></div>
        <button class="btn-check" id="btn-0" onclick="check(0,'B')" disabled>Check answer</button>
      </div>
    </div>
  </div>
</div>

<div class="q-panel" id="qp-1">
  <div class="math-layout">
    <div class="problem-panel">
      <div class="panel-label">Two-way table</div>
      <table class="two-way">
        <tr><th></th><th>Prefers cats</th><th>Prefers dogs</th><th>Total</th></tr>
        <tr><td><strong>Under 30</strong></td><td>45</td><td>55</td><td class="total">100</td></tr>
        <tr><td><strong>30 and over</strong></td><td>30</td><td>70</td><td class="total">100</td></tr>
        <tr><td class="total">Total</td><td class="total">75</td><td class="total">125</td><td class="total">200</td></tr>
      </table>
      <div class="hint">For independence, check whether P(prefers cats | under 30) = P(prefers cats | 30+). Under 30: 45/100=45%. 30+: 30/100=30%. They differ → associated.</div>
    </div>
    <div class="q-panel-inner">
      <div class="q-label">Question 2 · Association</div>
      <div class="q-text">Do age group and pet preference appear to be <strong>associated</strong>?</div>
      <div class="opts" id="opts-1">
        <div class="opt" onclick="pick(1,this,'A')"><span class="opt-l">A</span>No — equal numbers of people were surveyed in each age group.</div>
        <div class="opt" onclick="pick(1,this,'B')"><span class="opt-l">B</span>Yes — a higher percentage of under-30s prefer cats compared to the 30+ group.</div>
        <div class="opt" onclick="pick(1,this,'C')"><span class="opt-l">C</span>No — more people overall prefer dogs.</div>
        <div class="opt" onclick="pick(1,this,'D')"><span class="opt-l">D</span>Yes — there are 200 total people surveyed.</div>
      </div>
      <div class="q-actions">
        <div class="feedback" id="fb-1-ok"><strong>Correct!</strong><div class="fb-work">Under 30: P(cats) = 45/100 = 45%<br>30+: P(cats) = 30/100 = 30%<br>Conditional distributions DIFFER → variables are associated ✓<br><br>Equal sample sizes (A) is irrelevant to association. More people preferring dogs overall (C) doesn't address whether age and preference are linked.</div></div>
        <div class="feedback" id="fb-1-fail"><strong>Not quite.</strong> To check association, compare conditional distributions: what percent of each age group prefers cats? Under 30: 45%. 30+: 30%. These differ — so age and preference are associated.<div class="fb-work">45% vs 30% → distributions differ → associated</div></div>
        <button class="btn-check" id="btn-1" onclick="check(1,'B')" disabled>Check answer</button>
      </div>
    </div>
  </div>
</div>

<div class="q-panel" id="qp-2">
  <div class="math-layout">
    <div class="problem-panel">
      <div class="panel-label">Residual plot context</div>
      <div class="problem-text">A researcher fits a linear model to data about temperature (x) and ice cream sales (y). The residual plot shows residuals that are negative for low x, positive for middle x, and negative again for high x — forming a curve.</div>
      <div class="hint">A systematic curved pattern in a residual plot means the linear model misses a real curved relationship in the data. The researcher should try a quadratic or other nonlinear model instead.</div>
    </div>
    <div class="q-panel-inner">
      <div class="q-label">Question 3 · Residual Plot Interpretation</div>
      <div class="q-text">What does the curved pattern in the residual plot suggest?</div>
      <div class="opts" id="opts-2">
        <div class="opt" onclick="pick(2,this,'A')"><span class="opt-l">A</span>The linear model is a good fit for the data.</div>
        <div class="opt" onclick="pick(2,this,'B')"><span class="opt-l">B</span>The data has no association between temperature and sales.</div>
        <div class="opt" onclick="pick(2,this,'C')"><span class="opt-l">C</span>A nonlinear model would better describe the relationship.</div>
        <div class="opt" onclick="pick(2,this,'D')"><span class="opt-l">D</span>The residuals confirm the linear model is appropriate.</div>
      </div>
      <div class="q-actions">
        <div class="feedback" id="fb-2-ok"><strong>Correct!</strong> A curved pattern in a residual plot means the linear model is systematically over- or under-predicting in different regions — there is structure the model isn't capturing. A nonlinear (e.g., quadratic) model would fit better. A good linear fit has residuals randomly scattered around zero with no visible pattern.</div>
        <div class="feedback" id="fb-2-fail"><strong>Not quite.</strong> In a residual plot, a curved/systematic pattern means the linear model is inadequate — it's missing a nonlinear relationship. What kind of model would better capture a curved relationship?<div class="fb-work">Curved residuals → try a nonlinear (quadratic) model</div></div>
        <button class="btn-check" id="btn-2" onclick="check(2,'C')" disabled>Check answer</button>
      </div>
    </div>
  </div>
</div>

