<div class="tag">SAT Math · Module 4 · Lesson 4.17</div>
<div class="lesson-title">Inference & Sampling</div>
<div class="lesson-sub">Master the logic of statistical inference — making population estimates from samples — and learn to evaluate the validity and scope of conclusions drawn from survey and experimental data.</div>
<div class="dur-row"><span><b>12 min</b> read</span><span><b>3</b> practice questions</span><span><b>+20 pts</b> on completion</span></div>

<div class="card">
  <div class="sec-title">From sample to population — the inference chain</div>
  <div class="body-text">Statistical inference lets us draw conclusions about a <strong>population</strong> based on a <strong>sample</strong>. The validity of these conclusions depends entirely on how the sample was selected.</div>
  <div class="concept-grid">
    <div class="c-card">
      <div class="c-title">Simple random sample (SRS)</div>
      <div class="c-body">Every member of the population has an equal chance of being selected. Results can be generalized to the population. The gold standard for surveys.</div>
    </div>
    <div class="c-card">
      <div class="c-title">Voluntary response bias</div>
      <div class="c-body">When people self-select into a survey (calling a hotline, clicking an online poll), strong opinions are over-represented. Results cannot be generalized.</div>
      <div class="c-ex">Online polls, call-in surveys → voluntary response bias</div>
    </div>
    <div class="c-card">
      <div class="c-title">Convenience sample</div>
      <div class="c-body">Selecting whoever is easiest to reach (students in one class, people at a mall). Not representative — can't generalize to the broader population.</div>
    </div>
    <div class="c-card">
      <div class="c-title">Undercoverage bias</div>
      <div class="c-body">When some groups in the population are less likely to be included in the sample than others. The sample systematically misses certain subgroups.</div>
    </div>
    <div class="c-card">
      <div class="c-title">Scope of inference — generalizability</div>
      <div class="c-body">You can only generalize results to the population from which the sample was randomly drawn. Broader claims beyond that population are not supported.</div>
      <div class="c-ex">Random sample of one school → can generalize to that school only, not all schools.</div>
    </div>
    <div class="c-card">
      <div class="c-title">Estimation from sample to population</div>
      <div class="c-body">If p% of a random sample has a property, we estimate p% of the population has it. This estimate applies only to the population the sample came from.</div>
      <div class="c-ex">40% of a random sample of 500 city residents → estimate 40% of all city residents.</div>
    </div>
  </div>
  <div class="warn-box">
    <div class="warn-label">The most common SAT inference traps</div>
    <div class="warn-text"><strong>Trap 1:</strong> Claiming the sample result is exactly equal to the population parameter (ignoring sampling variability). <strong>Trap 2:</strong> Generalizing beyond the population sampled (e.g., from one city to the whole country). <strong>Trap 3:</strong> Drawing causal conclusions from an observational study. <strong>Trap 4:</strong> Concluding causation from a biased sample.</div>
  </div>
</div>

<div class="card">
  <div class="sec-title">SAT strategy tips</div>
  <div class="tips-grid">
    <div class="tip"><div class="tip-title">Estimate counts from proportions</div><div class="tip-body">If 35% of a random sample of 200 prefer option A, and the city population is 50,000, estimate: 0.35 × 50,000 = 17,500 city residents prefer option A. This proportional extrapolation is valid only for random samples.</div></div>
    <div class="tip"><div class="tip-title">Always check how the sample was selected</div><div class="tip-body">Before evaluating any conclusion, identify the sampling method. Was it random? Who had a chance to respond? Non-random or voluntary samples cannot support population-wide conclusions — the SAT will test this every time.</div></div>
    <div class="tip"><div class="tip-title">Generalize only to the sampled population</div><div class="tip-body">If a study samples customers of one store, conclusions apply to customers of that store — not to all shoppers nationwide. The scope of conclusion must match the scope of sampling. Over-generalizing is always a wrong answer.</div></div>
    <div class="tip"><div class="tip-title">Larger sample → smaller margin of error</div><div class="tip-body">All else equal, larger samples produce more reliable estimates with narrower confidence intervals. The SAT may ask which of two study designs produces more reliable estimates — choose the one with the larger random sample.</div></div>
  </div>
</div>

