<div class="q-panel active" id="qp-0">
  <div class="math-layout">
    <div class="problem-panel">
      <div class="panel-label">Problem</div>
      <div class="problem-text">A random sample of 400 residents from a city of 120,000 was surveyed. 28% said they use public transportation daily.</div>
      <div class="hint">For a random sample, you can estimate the population proportion. Apply 28% to the city's total population of 120,000: 0.28 × 120,000 = 33,600.</div>
    </div>
    <div class="q-panel-inner">
      <div class="q-label">Question 1 · Population Estimate</div>
      <div class="q-text">Which is the best estimate of the number of city residents who use public transportation daily?</div>
      <div class="opts" id="opts-0">
        <div class="opt" onclick="pick(0,this,'A')"><span class="opt-l">A</span>112 residents</div>
        <div class="opt" onclick="pick(0,this,'B')"><span class="opt-l">B</span>28,000 residents</div>
        <div class="opt" onclick="pick(0,this,'C')"><span class="opt-l">C</span>33,600 residents</div>
        <div class="opt" onclick="pick(0,this,'D')"><span class="opt-l">D</span>400 residents</div>
      </div>
      <div class="q-actions">
        <div class="feedback" id="fb-0-ok"><strong>Correct! 33,600 residents</strong><div class="fb-work">Random sample → can estimate population proportion<br>Estimated count = 28% × 120,000 = 0.28 × 120,000 = 33,600 ✓<br><br>Option A (112) = 28% of the sample (400). Option B is a round number not derived correctly.</div></div>
        <div class="feedback" id="fb-0-fail"><strong>Not quite.</strong> Since the sample was random, apply the sample proportion to the full population: 28% of 120,000.<div class="fb-work">0.28 × 120,000 = 33,600</div></div>
        <button class="btn-check" id="btn-0" onclick="check(0,'C')" disabled>Check answer</button>
      </div>
    </div>
  </div>
</div>

<div class="q-panel" id="qp-1">
  <div class="math-layout">
    <div class="problem-panel">
      <div class="panel-label">Problem</div>
      <div class="problem-text">A researcher posts an online survey asking people whether they support a new local park. Of the 250 respondents, 82% said yes.</div>
      <div class="hint">This is a voluntary response sample — only people who chose to respond participated. Online surveys are subject to voluntary response bias. Who is most likely to click and respond?</div>
    </div>
    <div class="q-panel-inner">
      <div class="q-label">Question 2 · Sampling Bias</div>
      <div class="q-text">Which limitation most affects this survey's conclusions?</div>
      <div class="opts" id="opts-1">
        <div class="opt" onclick="pick(1,this,'A')"><span class="opt-l">A</span>The sample size of 250 is too small to draw any conclusions.</div>
        <div class="opt" onclick="pick(1,this,'B')"><span class="opt-l">B</span>Voluntary response bias — people with strong opinions (especially supporters) are more likely to respond, over-representing support for the park.</div>
        <div class="opt" onclick="pick(1,this,'C')"><span class="opt-l">C</span>The 82% result is too high to be credible.</div>
        <div class="opt" onclick="pick(1,this,'D')"><span class="opt-l">D</span>The survey should have asked more questions to get accurate results.</div>
      </div>
      <div class="q-actions">
        <div class="feedback" id="fb-1-ok"><strong>Correct!</strong> An online opt-in survey has voluntary response bias — the 250 people who chose to respond are not representative of all residents. People who strongly support the park are more likely to click and complete the survey, inflating the "yes" percentage. Option A is incorrect — 250 can be adequate for a random sample; the issue is how they were selected, not how many.</div>
        <div class="feedback" id="fb-1-fail"><strong>Not quite.</strong> The problem isn't sample size — it's how the sample was collected. What happens to an online survey where people self-select to participate?<div class="fb-work">Voluntary response → strong opinions over-represented → biased</div></div>
        <button class="btn-check" id="btn-1" onclick="check(1,'B')" disabled>Check answer</button>
      </div>
    </div>
  </div>
</div>

<div class="q-panel" id="qp-2">
  <div class="math-layout">
    <div class="problem-panel">
      <div class="panel-label">Problem</div>
      <div class="problem-text">Two schools each conducted a survey about students' sleep habits. School A used a random sample of 300 students; School B surveyed every student who attended a health class (120 students).</div>
      <div class="hint">Compare the two sampling methods: School A is random (can generalize to all students at that school). School B is a convenience sample (health class students may have different sleep habits than average).</div>
    </div>
    <div class="q-panel-inner">
      <div class="q-label">Question 3 · Comparing Survey Designs</div>
      <div class="q-text">Whose results can be more reliably generalized to their school's entire student population?</div>
      <div class="opts" id="opts-2">
        <div class="opt" onclick="pick(2,this,'A')"><span class="opt-l">A</span>School B, because 100% of health class students were surveyed.</div>
        <div class="opt" onclick="pick(2,this,'B')"><span class="opt-l">B</span>School A, because a random sample better represents the full student population.</div>
        <div class="opt" onclick="pick(2,this,'C')"><span class="opt-l">C</span>School A, because 300 is a larger sample than 120.</div>
        <div class="opt" onclick="pick(2,this,'D')"><span class="opt-l">D</span>Neither — neither study used a national random sample.</div>
      </div>
      <div class="q-actions">
        <div class="feedback" id="fb-2-ok"><strong>Correct! School A</strong> The reason is the random sampling method, not merely the larger size (B is also true but not the primary reason). School B's health class students are a convenience sample — health-conscious students may sleep differently from the average student, making the results unrepresentative. School A's random sample gives all students an equal chance of inclusion, so it best represents the full school. Option D is wrong — generalization to the school doesn't require a national sample.</div>
        <div class="feedback" id="fb-2-fail"><strong>Not quite.</strong> The key isn't sample size — it's how the sample was selected. School B surveyed health class students, who may not be representative of all students. Which sampling method gives all students an equal chance of inclusion?<div class="fb-work">Random sample → representative → can generalize to the school</div></div>
        <button class="btn-check" id="btn-2" onclick="check(2,'B')" disabled>Check answer</button>
      </div>
    </div>
  </div>
</div>

