<div class="lesson-title">Ratios, Rates & Proportions</div>
<div class="lesson-sub">Apply ratios and proportions to complex multi-step problems — mixture problems, work rates, speed-distance-time, and scaling — the applied contexts the calculator section emphasizes.</div>
<div class="dur-row"><span><b>13 min</b> read</span><span><b>3</b> practice questions</span><span><b>+20 pts</b> on completion</span></div>

<div class="card">
  <div class="sec-title">Advanced ratio and rate applications</div>
  <div class="types-grid">
    <div class="t-card">
      <div class="t-title">Mixture problems</div>
      <div class="t-body">Combine two substances with different concentrations/values. The total amount and total value must both be conserved. Set up two equations: quantity and value.</div>
      <div class="t-ex">Mix 30% and 70% solution to get 50%:<br>0.30x + 0.70(100−x) = 0.50(100)<br>Solve for x.</div>
    </div>
    <div class="t-card">
      <div class="t-title">Combined work rates</div>
      <div class="t-body">If A does a job in a hours and B does it in b hours, together they complete 1/a + 1/b of the job per hour. Time together = 1/(1/a + 1/b) = ab/(a+b).</div>
      <div class="t-ex">A: 6 hr, B: 4 hr<br>Together: ab/(a+b) = 24/10 = 2.4 hours</div>
    </div>
    <div class="t-card">
      <div class="t-title">Speed-distance-time</div>
      <div class="t-body">d = rt. Average speed = total distance / total time. For round trips where speeds differ, calculate each leg's time separately, then find total d and total t.</div>
      <div class="t-ex">60 mph out, 40 mph back, 120 mi each way:<br>Time out = 2 hr, time back = 3 hr<br>Avg speed = 240/5 = 48 mph</div>
    </div>
    <div class="t-card">
      <div class="t-title">Scaling with proportions</div>
      <div class="t-body">When all dimensions scale by factor k: perimeter/length scales by k, area scales by k², volume scales by k³. State which dimension changed and use the correct power.</div>
    </div>
  </div>
  <div class="example-box">
    <div class="example-label">Worked example — mixture problem</div>
    <div class="example-text">
      A chemist has a 20% acid solution and an 80% acid solution. How many liters of each should be mixed to make 60 liters of a 50% acid solution?<br><br>
      <span class="fb-work">Let x = liters of 20% solution · (60 − x) = liters of 80% solution</span><br>
      <span class="fb-work">0.20x + 0.80(60 − x) = 0.50(60)</span><br>
      <span class="fb-work">0.20x + 48 − 0.80x = 30</span><br>
      <span class="fb-work">−0.60x = −18 → x = 30 liters of 20% solution</span><br>
      30 liters of 20% + 30 liters of 80% → 60 liters of 50%
    </div>
  </div>
</div>

<div class="card">
