      Simple interest: I = Prt &nbsp;·&nbsp; A = P(1 + rt)<br>
      Compound interest: A = P(1 + r/n)ⁿᵗ<br>
      Total cost with tax: C = price × (1 + tax rate)<br>
      Final price after markup then discount: P × (1+m) × (1−d)
    </div>
  </div>
  <div class="types-grid">
    <div class="t-card">
      <div class="t-title">Simple vs. compound interest</div>
      <div class="t-body">Simple: interest calculated only on principal. Compound: interest calculated on principal plus accumulated interest. Compound always yields more over time.</div>
      <div class="t-ex">$1,000 at 5% for 3 yr:<br>Simple: I = 1000×0.05×3 = $150<br>Compound annually: 1000×(1.05)³ = $1,157.63</div>
    </div>
    <div class="t-card">
      <div class="t-title">Sequential discounts and markups</div>
      <div class="t-body">Apply each multiplier in sequence — never add percentages. A 20% markup followed by a 20% discount is NOT 0% change: 1.20 × 0.80 = 0.96 → net −4%.</div>
      <div class="t-ex">Item: $100 · +30% markup: $130<br>−15% discount: $130 × 0.85 = $110.50<br>Net change: +10.5%, not +15%</div>
    </div>
    <div class="t-card">
      <div class="t-title">Tax, tip, and total cost</div>
      <div class="t-body">Add tax/tip percentage as a multiplier to the pre-tax price. To find original price given total including tax: divide total by (1 + tax rate).</div>
      <div class="t-ex">Meal $45, 18% tip, 8% tax:<br>$45 × 1.18 = $53.10 (with tip)<br>$53.10 × 1.08 = $57.35 (with tax on tip+meal)</div>
    </div>
    <div class="t-card">
      <div class="t-title">Finding original before percentage</div>
      <div class="t-body">After applying a percentage change, reverse it by dividing. After a 35% markup the price is $270: original = 270 ÷ 1.35 = $200. Never subtract the percent from the result.</div>
    </div>
  </div>
</div>

<div class="card">
  <div class="sec-title">SAT strategy tips</div>
  <div class="tips-grid">
    <div class="tip"><div class="tip-title">Compound interest: identify all 4 variables</div><div class="tip-body">Before computing A = P(1 + r/n)ⁿᵗ, explicitly label P (principal), r (annual rate as decimal), n (compoundings per year), and t (years). Misidentifying n is the most common error — monthly means n=12, quarterly means n=4.</div></div>
    <div class="tip"><div class="tip-title">Sequential changes: multiply, never add</div><div class="tip-body">For any sequence of percent changes, multiply the multipliers in order. Never add or subtract percentages. A 15% increase then a 10% decrease: 1.15 × 0.90 = 1.035 → net +3.5%.</div></div>
    <div class="tip"><div class="tip-title">Tax/tip order matters</div><div class="tip-body">If tip is calculated on the pre-tax amount and tax on the post-tip amount (or vice versa), the calculation differs. Read the problem carefully to identify what percentage applies to what base.</div></div>
    <div class="tip"><div class="tip-title">Simple interest: linear; compound: exponential</div><div class="tip-body">Simple interest grows linearly (straight line on a graph). Compound interest grows exponentially (curved). A = P(1+rt) is linear in t. A = P(1+r)ᵗ is exponential in t. The SAT tests which model applies.</div></div>
  </div>
</div>

