<div class="lesson-title">Functions & Transformations</div>
<div class="lesson-sub">Master every transformation of a function — shifts, reflections, stretches, and compressions — and apply them to any function type: linear, quadratic, exponential, and absolute value.</div>
<div class="dur-row"><span><b>13 min</b> read</span><span><b>3</b> practice questions</span><span><b>+20 pts</b> on completion</span></div>

<div class="card">
  <div class="sec-title">Complete transformation reference</div>
  <table class="trans-table">
    <tr><th>Transformation</th><th>Equation</th><th>Effect on graph</th></tr>
    <tr><td>f(x) + k</td><td>k &gt; 0</td><td class="desc">Shifts UP by k units. Every y-value increases by k.</td></tr>
    <tr><td>f(x) − k</td><td>k &gt; 0</td><td class="desc">Shifts DOWN by k units. Every y-value decreases by k.</td></tr>
    <tr><td>f(x + h)</td><td>h &gt; 0</td><td class="desc">Shifts LEFT by h units. (Counter-intuitive — adding to x shifts left.)</td></tr>
    <tr><td>f(x − h)</td><td>h &gt; 0</td><td class="desc">Shifts RIGHT by h units.</td></tr>
    <tr><td>−f(x)</td><td></td><td class="desc">Reflects over the x-axis. Every y-value changes sign.</td></tr>
    <tr><td>f(−x)</td><td></td><td class="desc">Reflects over the y-axis. Every x-value changes sign.</td></tr>
    <tr><td>a·f(x)</td><td>a &gt; 1</td><td class="desc">Vertical stretch by factor a. Graph taller/narrower.</td></tr>
    <tr><td>a·f(x)</td><td>0 &lt; a &lt; 1</td><td class="desc">Vertical compression by factor a. Graph shorter/wider.</td></tr>
    <tr><td>f(bx)</td><td>b &gt; 1</td><td class="desc">Horizontal compression (faster period). Graph compressed toward y-axis.</td></tr>
    <tr><td>f(bx)</td><td>0 &lt; b &lt; 1</td><td class="desc">Horizontal stretch. Graph stretched away from y-axis.</td></tr>
  </table>
  <div class="example-box">
    <div class="example-label">Worked example — combining transformations</div>
    <div class="example-text">
      The graph of y = f(x) passes through (2, 5). Find the corresponding point on y = −2f(x − 3) + 1.<br><br>
      <span class="fb-work">Start with point (2, 5) on f(x).</span><br>
      <span class="fb-work">f(x − 3): shift right 3 → x becomes 2 + 3 = 5</span><br>
      <span class="fb-work">−2f(...): reflect and stretch → y becomes −2(5) = −10</span><br>
      <span class="fb-work">+1: shift up 1 → y becomes −10 + 1 = −9</span><br>
      New point: <strong>(5, −9)</strong>
    </div>
  </div>
</div>

<div class="card">
  <div class="sec-title">SAT strategy tips</div>
  <div class="tips-grid">
    <div class="tip"><div class="tip-title">Horizontal shifts are counterintuitive — always double-check</div><div class="tip-body">f(x + 3) shifts LEFT by 3, not right. f(x − 3) shifts RIGHT by 3. To remember: set the inside expression equal to zero — x + 3 = 0 means x = −3, so the shift is to the left. This counterintuitive direction is tested constantly.</div></div>
    <div class="tip"><div class="tip-title">Track a single point through combined transformations</div><div class="tip-body">For any combined transformation, pick the simplest point from the original graph and apply each transformation in order to that point. This is faster and more reliable than trying to interpret the combined formula all at once.</div></div>
    <div class="tip"><div class="tip-title">Vertical changes: affect y, apply outside the function</div><div class="tip-body">Anything added, subtracted, or multiplied OUTSIDE f(...) changes y. Anything inside f(...) changes x. Keep this rule clear: outside → vertical effect, inside → horizontal effect (often with opposite sign).</div></div>
    <div class="tip"><div class="tip-title">Absolute value transformation: |f(x)| reflects negative part</div><div class="tip-body">y = |f(x)| takes any part of the graph below the x-axis and reflects it above. Any y-value that was negative becomes positive. Parts already above the x-axis stay unchanged.</div></div>
  </div>
</div>

<div class="sec-title" style="margin-bottom:.75rem">Practice questions</div>
<div class="q-tabs">
  <button class="q-tab active" onclick="switchQ(0,this)">Question 1</button>
  <button class="q-tab" onclick="switchQ(1,this)">Question 2</button>
  <button class="q-tab" onclick="switchQ(2,this)">Question 3</button>
</div>

<div class="q-panel active" id="qp-0">
  <div class="math-layout">
    <div class="problem-panel">
      <div class="panel-label">Problem</div>
      <div class="problem-text">The graph of f(x) = x² has vertex at (0, 0). Consider:</div>
      <span class="math-eq">g(x) = (x + 4)² − 6</span>
      <div class="hint">f(x+4) shifts left 4: vertex moves from x=0 to x=−4. The −6 shifts down 6: vertex moves from y=0 to y=−6. New vertex: (−4, −6).</div>
    </div>
    <div class="q-panel-inner">
      <div class="q-label">Question 1 · Vertex after Transformation</div>
      <div class="q-text">What is the <strong>vertex</strong> of g(x)?</div>
      <div class="opts" id="opts-0">
        <div class="opt" onclick="pick(0,this,'A')"><span class="opt-l">A</span>(4, −6)</div>
        <div class="opt" onclick="pick(0,this,'B')"><span class="opt-l">B</span>(−4, 6)</div>
        <div class="opt" onclick="pick(0,this,'C')"><span class="opt-l">C</span>(−4, −6)</div>
        <div class="opt" onclick="pick(0,this,'D')"><span class="opt-l">D</span>(4, 6)</div>
      </div>
      <div class="q-actions">
        <div class="feedback" id="fb-0-ok"><strong>Correct! (−4, −6)</strong><div class="fb-work">(x+4)² = (x−(−4))² → shifts LEFT 4 → vertex x = −4<br>−6 outside → shifts DOWN 6 → vertex y = −6<br>Vertex: (−4, −6) ✓<br><br>Common trap: (x+4)² makes students think vertex is at x=+4. Set x+4=0 → x=−4.</div></div>
        <div class="feedback" id="fb-0-fail"><strong>Not quite.</strong> f(x+4) shifts the graph LEFT (set x+4=0 → x=−4). The −6 outside shifts DOWN. What does that make the vertex?<div class="fb-work">Left 4, down 6 → vertex (−4, −6)</div></div>
        <button class="btn-check" id="btn-0" onclick="check(0,'C')" disabled>Check answer</button>
      </div>
    </div>
  </div>
</div>

<div class="q-panel" id="qp-1">
  <div class="math-layout">
    <div class="problem-panel">
      <div class="panel-label">Problem</div>
      <div class="problem-text">The graph of y = f(x) passes through the point (−3, 8). Consider:</div>
      <span class="math-eq">h(x) = −f(x) + 5</span>
      <div class="hint">Apply transformations to the point (−3, 8). First −f(x): reflects y → y becomes −8. Then +5: shifts up 5 → y becomes −8+5 = −3. x-coordinate is unchanged by these vertical transformations.</div>
    </div>
    <div class="q-panel-inner">
      <div class="q-label">Question 2 · Tracking a Point</div>
      <div class="q-text">What point must lie on the graph of <strong>h(x) = −f(x) + 5</strong>?</div>
      <div class="opts" id="opts-1">
        <div class="opt" onclick="pick(1,this,'A')"><span class="opt-l">A</span>(−3, 3)</div>
        <div class="opt" onclick="pick(1,this,'B')"><span class="opt-l">B</span>(3, −3)</div>
        <div class="opt" onclick="pick(1,this,'C')"><span class="opt-l">C</span>(−3, −3)</div>
        <div class="opt" onclick="pick(1,this,'D')"><span class="opt-l">D</span>(3, 13)</div>
      </div>
      <div class="q-actions">
        <div class="feedback" id="fb-1-ok"><strong>Correct! (−3, −3)</strong><div class="fb-work">Original point: (−3, 8)<br>−f(x): y → −8 · (x stays −3)<br>+5: y → −8+5 = −3<br>New point: (−3, −3) ✓<br><br>Verify: h(−3) = −f(−3)+5 = −8+5 = −3 ✓</div></div>
        <div class="feedback" id="fb-1-fail"><strong>Not quite.</strong> Both −f(x) and +5 are outside the function, so they affect y only. x stays −3. Apply to y=8: first negate, then add 5.<div class="fb-work">y: 8 → −8 → −8+5 = −3 · Point: (−3, −3)</div></div>
        <button class="btn-check" id="btn-1" onclick="check(1,'C')" disabled>Check answer</button>
      </div>
    </div>
  </div>
</div>

<div class="q-panel" id="qp-2">
  <div class="math-layout">
    <div class="problem-panel">
      <div class="panel-label">Problem</div>
      <div class="problem-text">The function f(x) = 2ˣ is transformed to produce:</div>
      <span class="math-eq">g(x) = 2^(x − 1) + 3</span>
      <div class="hint">Horizontal shift: x−1 inside → shifts right 1. So the y-intercept of f (which was at x=0) moves to x=1. Vertical shift: +3 outside → shifts up 3. The horizontal asymptote of f (y=0) moves to y=3.</div>
    </div>
    <div class="q-panel-inner">
      <div class="q-label">Question 3 · Exponential Transformation</div>
      <div class="q-text">What is the <strong>horizontal asymptote</strong> of g(x)?</div>
      <div class="opts" id="opts-2">
        <div class="opt" onclick="pick(2,this,'A')"><span class="opt-l">A</span>y = 0</div>
        <div class="opt" onclick="pick(2,this,'B')"><span class="opt-l">B</span>y = 1</div>
        <div class="opt" onclick="pick(2,this,'C')"><span class="opt-l">C</span>y = 3</div>
        <div class="opt" onclick="pick(2,this,'D')"><span class="opt-l">D</span>y = −1</div>
      </div>
      <div class="q-actions">
        <div class="feedback" id="fb-2-ok"><strong>Correct! y = 3</strong><div class="fb-work">f(x) = 2ˣ has horizontal asymptote y = 0 (as x→−∞, 2ˣ→0)<br>g(x) = 2^(x−1) + 3: the +3 shifts the entire graph UP by 3<br>New asymptote: y = 0 + 3 = 3 ✓<br><br>The horizontal shift (x−1) moves the graph right but doesn't change the asymptote. Only the vertical shift (+3) changes the asymptote.</div></div>
        <div class="feedback" id="fb-2-fail"><strong>Not quite.</strong> The original f(x) = 2ˣ approaches y = 0 as x→−∞. Adding +3 outside shifts the entire graph up by 3 — including the asymptote. What does the asymptote become?<div class="fb-work">y = 0 + 3 = 3</div></div>
        <button class="btn-check" id="btn-2" onclick="check(2,'C')" disabled>Check answer</button>
      </div>
    </div>
  </div>
</div>

