<div class="lesson-title">Quadratic & Polynomial Applications</div>
<div class="lesson-sub">Apply quadratic and polynomial skills to the richest real-world contexts — area and dimension problems, number relationships, projectile motion, and discriminant applications.</div>
<div class="dur-row"><span><b>13 min</b> read</span><span><b>3</b> practice questions</span><span><b>+20 pts</b> on completion</span></div>

<div class="card">
  <div class="sec-title">Real-world quadratic setups</div>
  <div class="app-grid">
    <div class="app-card">
      <div class="app-title">Area and dimension problems</div>
      <div class="app-body">Express length and width in terms of one variable using a constraint, write the area as a product, set equal to a given area, and solve the resulting quadratic.</div>
      <div class="app-ex">Rectangle: l = x+3, w = x. Area = 40<br>x(x+3) = 40 → x²+3x−40 = 0<br>(x+8)(x−5) = 0 → x = 5</div>
    </div>
    <div class="app-card">
      <div class="app-title">Number relationship problems</div>
      <div class="app-body">Two numbers differ by some amount and their product is given. Let the numbers be x and (x + d), set their product equal to the given value, and solve.</div>
      <div class="app-ex">Two consecutive even integers, product 80:<br>n(n+2) = 80 → n²+2n−80 = 0<br>(n+10)(n−8) = 0 → n = 8 (positive)</div>
    </div>
    <div class="app-card">
      <div class="app-title">Discriminant — number of solutions</div>
      <div class="app-body">Discriminant Δ = b²−4ac determines how many real solutions exist. Δ &gt; 0: two real solutions. Δ = 0: one solution (repeated). Δ &lt; 0: no real solutions.</div>
      <div class="app-ex">x²+kx+9 = 0 has one solution when:<br>k²−36 = 0 → k = ±6</div>
    </div>
    <div class="app-card">
      <div class="app-title">Polynomial remainder theorem</div>
      <div class="app-body">If a polynomial p(x) is divided by (x − a), the remainder equals p(a). If p(a) = 0, then (x − a) is a factor. Use this to verify zeros or find missing coefficients.</div>
      <div class="app-ex">p(x) = x³ − 2x + k. If (x−3) is a factor:<br>p(3) = 27−6+k = 0 → k = −21</div>
    </div>
  </div>
  <div class="example-box">
    <div class="example-label">Worked example — discriminant application</div>
    <div class="example-text">
      For what values of k does kx² − 6x + 3 = 0 have no real solutions?<br><br>
      <span class="fb-work">Δ = (−6)² − 4(k)(3) = 36 − 12k</span><br>
      <span class="fb-work">No real solutions when Δ &lt; 0:</span><br>
      <span class="fb-work">36 − 12k &lt; 0 → 12k &gt; 36 → k &gt; 3</span><br>
      Also need k ≠ 0 (otherwise not quadratic). Answer: k &gt; 3.
    </div>
  </div>
</div>

<div class="card">
