    <div class="tip"><div class="tip-title">Draw and label dimensions in area problems</div><div class="tip-body">Before writing any equation, sketch the shape and label both dimensions with expressions in one variable. This prevents misidentifying which dimension is length and which is width, and ensures the area equation is set up correctly.</div></div>
    <div class="tip"><div class="tip-title">Discriminant = b²−4ac, not (b²−4ac)/2a</div><div class="tip-body">The discriminant is just the expression under the square root in the quadratic formula: b²−4ac. You only divide by 2a when finding the actual roots. For questions about the number of solutions, compute b²−4ac and check its sign.</div></div>
    <div class="tip"><div class="tip-title">Remainder theorem: evaluate, don't divide</div><div class="tip-body">To find the remainder when p(x) is divided by (x−a), just compute p(a). This is always faster than performing polynomial long division. If the question asks whether (x−a) is a factor, check if p(a) = 0.</div></div>
    <div class="tip"><div class="tip-title">Reject negative solutions for lengths/times</div><div class="tip-body">When a quadratic gives two solutions, always check context. Lengths, times, counts, and prices must be non-negative. Reject any solution that's negative or doesn't make physical sense for the problem.</div></div>
