<div class="lesson-title">Geometry Applications</div>
<div class="lesson-sub">Apply all geometry skills to complex multi-step real-world problems — architectural design, surveying, packaging, and navigation — where multiple geometry concepts combine in a single question.</div>
<div class="dur-row"><span><b>13 min</b> read</span><span><b>3</b> practice questions</span><span><b>+20 pts</b> on completion</span></div>

<div class="card">
  <div class="sec-title">Combining geometry concepts</div>
  <div class="body-text">The most challenging SAT geometry questions require combining multiple concepts — for example, using trigonometry inside a volume calculation, or applying similar triangles within a coordinate geometry problem. The key is identifying which tools are needed before starting any calculation.</div>
  <div class="app-grid">
    <div class="app-card">
      <div class="app-title">Trig in 3D problems</div>
      <div class="app-body">Use trig ratios to find missing lengths in cross-sections of 3D figures. Find the height of a cone from a slant height and angle, or the diagonal of a box.</div>
      <div class="app-ex">Box 8×6×h. Space diagonal d:<br>d = √(8²+6²+h²) = √(100+h²)</div>
    </div>
    <div class="app-card">
      <div class="app-title">Scale and proportion in geometry</div>
      <div class="app-body">When dimensions scale by k: lengths scale by k, areas by k², volumes by k³. Common SAT question: a shape is scaled by factor k — how does the perimeter, area, or volume change?</div>
    </div>
    <div class="app-card">
      <div class="app-title">Circles and triangles combined</div>
      <div class="app-body">Many problems combine a circle with an inscribed or circumscribed polygon. The radius connects to the polygon's vertices or sides. Draw the radius to a key point and look for right angles.</div>
      <div class="app-ex">Equilateral triangle inscribed in circle of r=6:<br>Side = r√3 = 6√3</div>
    </div>
    <div class="app-card">
      <div class="app-title">Coordinate geometry + distance</div>
      <div class="app-body">Find the distance between a point and a line, the area of a polygon from coordinates, or whether a point lies inside a circle. These combine formulas from different geometry topics.</div>
    </div>
  </div>
  <div class="example-box">
    <div class="example-label">Worked example — multi-step geometry</div>
    <div class="example-text">
      A right circular cone has a slant height of 13 cm and a base radius of 5 cm. Find the volume.<br><br>
      <span class="fb-work">Step 1: Find height using Pythagorean theorem.</span><br>
      <span class="fb-work">h² + r² = l² → h² + 25 = 169 → h² = 144 → h = 12 cm</span><br>
      <span class="fb-work">Step 2: V = ⅓πr²h = ⅓π(25)(12) = 100π cm³</span>
    </div>
  </div>
</div>

<div class="card">
  <div class="sec-title">SAT strategy tips</div>
  <div class="tips-grid">
    <div class="tip"><div class="tip-title">Identify required concepts before calculating</div><div class="tip-body">Read the entire problem and list which geometry concepts are needed. Multi-step problems often require: (1) a trig ratio or Pythagorean theorem to find a length, then (2) that length in a volume or area formula. Doing step 2 before step 1 is the most common error.</div></div>
    <div class="tip"><div class="tip-title">Label every measurement on your diagram</div><div class="tip-body">Even in calculator section geometry, drawing and labeling a diagram is faster than holding dimensions in your head. Write all given measurements and intermediary results on the figure as you find them.</div></div>
    <div class="tip"><div class="tip-title">Slant height ≠ height in cones</div><div class="tip-body">The slant height l is the distance along the cone's surface from apex to base edge. The height h is the perpendicular distance from apex to base. They're related by h² + r² = l². Volume and surface area formulas use height h, not slant height l.</div></div>
    <div class="tip"><div class="tip-title">The space diagonal of a box uses all three dimensions</div><div class="tip-body">The longest diagonal through a rectangular box (from one corner to the opposite corner) equals √(l² + w² + h²). This is the Pythagorean theorem applied twice — first to find the face diagonal, then using that as a leg.</div></div>
