<div class="lesson-title">Mixed Problem Solving</div>
<div class="lesson-sub">The final lesson brings together all four modules — reading, writing, algebra, and data — in mixed, multi-concept problems that mirror the pace and variety of the real digital SAT.</div>
<div class="dur-row"><span><b>15 min</b> read</span><span><b>3</b> practice questions</span><span><b>+25 pts</b> on completion</span></div>

<div class="card">
  <div class="sec-title">How the SAT mixes concepts</div>
  <div class="body-text">On the real SAT, the hardest questions require you to recognize which concept applies, translate a word problem into the right mathematical structure, and execute cleanly. Here are the most important cross-topic combinations tested.</div>
  <div class="strategy-grid">
    <div class="strat-card">
      <div class="strat-title">Algebra + Geometry</div>
      <div class="strat-body">Set up an equation from a geometric constraint (perimeter, area, angle sum), then solve the algebra. Or use coordinate geometry to find geometric properties.</div>
    </div>
    <div class="strat-card">
      <div class="strat-title">Exponential + Statistics</div>
      <div class="strat-body">Fit an exponential model to real data, then interpret the model's parameters in context. Or identify whether a table shows linear or exponential growth before modeling.</div>
    </div>
    <div class="strat-card">
      <div class="strat-title">Proportions + Percent change</div>
      <div class="strat-body">Multi-step problems that combine ratio setup with percentage calculations — markups, conversions, and rate comparisons all in one problem.</div>
    </div>
    <div class="strat-card">
      <div class="strat-title">Systems + Inequalities</div>
      <div class="strat-body">Real-world constraints written as a mixed system (some equations, some inequalities) requiring substitution or test-a-point strategies to find the valid region.</div>
    </div>
    <div class="strat-card">
      <div class="strat-title">Functions + Transformations</div>
      <div class="strat-body">Given a graph of f(x), identify what transformation produces g(x), or find specific values of a transformed function using points from the original.</div>
    </div>
    <div class="strat-card">
      <div class="strat-title">Statistics + Inference</div>
      <div class="strat-body">Calculate a statistic from a sample, then evaluate whether the conclusion drawn (generalization, causation, margin of error) is valid.</div>
    </div>
  </div>
</div>

<div class="card">
  <div class="sec-title">Final exam strategy</div>
  <div class="tips-grid">
    <div class="tip"><div class="tip-title">Read the question before the problem</div><div class="tip-body">On multi-step problems, reading the question first tells you what you're solving for. This focuses your attention and prevents you from calculating things you don't need.</div></div>
    <div class="tip"><div class="tip-title">Label variables, write equations, then calculate</div><div class="tip-body">Every word problem requires three steps: (1) define variables, (2) write equations or inequalities, (3) solve. Students who skip to calculation make avoidable errors. The calculator helps with step 3 only.</div></div>
    <div class="tip"><div class="tip-title">Verify your answer makes sense</div><div class="tip-body">After solving, ask: is the answer reasonable? A negative length, a probability over 1, or a population that shrank when it was supposed to grow — all signal an error. Budget 5 seconds to sanity-check every answer.</div></div>
    <div class="tip"><div class="tip-title">Don't get stuck — use process of elimination</div><div class="tip-body">If a question is taking too long, eliminate obviously wrong answers and make an educated guess. Then mark it and move on. On the digital SAT, every question has equal weight — don't spend 5 minutes on one question at the expense of three others.</div></div>
  </div>
</div>

<div class="sec-title" style="margin-bottom:.75rem">Final practice questions</div>
<div class="q-tabs">
  <button class="q-tab active" onclick="switchQ(0,this)">Question 1</button>
  <button class="q-tab" onclick="switchQ(1,this)">Question 2</button>
  <button class="q-tab" onclick="switchQ(2,this)">Question 3</button>
</div>

<div class="q-panel active" id="qp-0">
  <div class="math-layout">
    <div class="problem-panel">
      <div class="panel-label">Multi-concept problem</div>
      <div class="problem-text">A square has side length s. The side is increased by 20%, creating a larger square.</div>
      <div class="hint">New side = 1.2s. New area = (1.2s)² = 1.44s². Original area = s². Percent increase = (1.44s² − s²)/s² × 100 = 44%.</div>
    </div>
    <div class="q-panel-inner">
      <div class="q-label">Question 1 · Geometry + Percentages</div>
      <div class="q-text">By what percent does the <strong>area</strong> of the square increase?</div>
      <div class="opts" id="opts-0">
        <div class="opt" onclick="pick(0,this,'A')"><span class="opt-l">A</span>20%</div>
        <div class="opt" onclick="pick(0,this,'B')"><span class="opt-l">B</span>40%</div>
        <div class="opt" onclick="pick(0,this,'C')"><span class="opt-l">C</span>44%</div>
        <div class="opt" onclick="pick(0,this,'D')"><span class="opt-l">D</span>24%</div>
      </div>
      <div class="q-actions">
        <div class="feedback" id="fb-0-ok"><strong>Correct! 44%</strong><div class="fb-work">New side = 1.2s<br>New area = (1.2s)² = 1.44s²<br>Original area = s²<br>% increase = (1.44s² − s²)/s² × 100<br>= 0.44 × 100 = 44% ✓<br><br>Key insight: a 20% increase in length → 1.2² = 1.44 → 44% increase in area. Linear and area scales are different!</div></div>
        <div class="feedback" id="fb-0-fail"><strong>Not quite.</strong> Area scales as the square of the linear dimension. New side = 1.2s → new area = (1.2s)² = 1.44s². The area increases by 44%, not 20% × 2 = 40%.<div class="fb-work">(1.2)² = 1.44 → 44% area increase</div></div>
        <button class="btn-check" id="btn-0" onclick="check(0,'C')" disabled>Check answer</button>
      </div>
    </div>
  </div>
</div>

<div class="q-panel" id="qp-1">
  <div class="math-layout">
    <div class="problem-panel">
      <div class="panel-label">Multi-concept problem</div>
      <div class="problem-text">A researcher randomly surveyed 500 visitors to a national park. 35% said they visited the park more than 3 times per year. The park receives approximately 180,000 visitors per year.</div>
      <div class="problem-text" style="margin-top:.5rem;">The researcher concluded: "Visiting the park more than 3 times per year causes visitors to develop stronger environmental values."</div>
      <div class="hint">This question combines inference (was the sample valid?) with study design (can an observational survey establish causation?). Identify both potential flaws.</div>
    </div>
    <div class="q-panel-inner">
      <div class="q-label">Question 2 · Statistics + Inference</div>
      <div class="q-text">Which best identifies a flaw in the researcher's conclusion?</div>
      <div class="opts" id="opts-1">
        <div class="opt" onclick="pick(1,this,'A')"><span class="opt-l">A</span>The sample size of 500 is too small to draw any conclusions.</div>
        <div class="opt" onclick="pick(1,this,'B')"><span class="opt-l">B</span>A survey cannot establish causation — frequent visitors may already hold stronger environmental values before visiting more.</div>
        <div class="opt" onclick="pick(1,this,'C')"><span class="opt-l">C</span>The estimate of 35% cannot be applied to the full 180,000 visitors.</div>
        <div class="opt" onclick="pick(1,this,'D')"><span class="opt-l">D</span>The survey should have been conducted online for more responses.</div>
      </div>
      <div class="q-actions">
        <div class="feedback" id="fb-1-ok"><strong>Correct!</strong> The fundamental flaw is that an observational survey cannot establish causation. The researcher observed an association between visit frequency and environmental values — but this doesn't mean visiting more caused the values. People who already have strong environmental values may choose to visit more. This is the classic correlation ≠ causation error. A (sample size) is wrong — 500 is a reasonable sample. C is wrong — a random sample can be used to estimate population proportions. D is irrelevant and would make the sample worse (voluntary response bias).</div>
        <div class="feedback" id="fb-1-fail"><strong>Not quite.</strong> The researcher used the word "causes" — but from an observational survey, can you establish causation? What alternative explanation might exist for the association?<div class="fb-work">Survey shows association, not causation. Confounding possible.</div></div>
        <button class="btn-check" id="btn-1" onclick="check(1,'B')" disabled>Check answer</button>
      </div>
    </div>
  </div>
</div>

<div class="q-panel" id="qp-2">
  <div class="math-layout">
    <div class="problem-panel">
      <div class="panel-label">Multi-concept problem</div>
      <div class="problem-text">A company's profit P (in thousands of dollars) after t years is modeled by:</div>
      <span class="math-eq">P(t) = −2t² + 16t − 24</span>
      <div class="hint">Maximum profit: find vertex at t = −16/(2×−2) = 4 years. Profit becomes positive when P(t) > 0: factor −2t²+16t−24 > 0 → −2(t²−8t+12) > 0 → −2(t−2)(t−6) > 0. Positive when 2 &lt; t &lt; 6.</div>
    </div>
    <div class="q-panel-inner">
      <div class="q-label">Question 3 · Algebra + Interpretation</div>
      <div class="q-text">During which time interval is the company <strong>profitable</strong> (P &gt; 0)?</div>
      <div class="opts" id="opts-2">
        <div class="opt" onclick="pick(2,this,'A')"><span class="opt-l">A</span>t &lt; 2 and t &gt; 6</div>
        <div class="opt" onclick="pick(2,this,'B')"><span class="opt-l">B</span>2 &lt; t &lt; 6</div>
        <div class="opt" onclick="pick(2,this,'C')"><span class="opt-l">C</span>0 &lt; t &lt; 8</div>
        <div class="opt" onclick="pick(2,this,'D')"><span class="opt-l">D</span>t &gt; 4</div>
      </div>
      <div class="q-actions">
        <div class="feedback" id="fb-2-ok"><strong>Correct! 2 &lt; t &lt; 6</strong><div class="fb-work">P(t) > 0: −2t²+16t−24 > 0<br>Divide by −2 (flip inequality): t²−8t+12 &lt; 0<br>Factor: (t−2)(t−6) &lt; 0<br>Negative between roots → 2 &lt; t &lt; 6 ✓<br><br>Verify: P(4) = −32+64−24 = 8 &gt; 0 ✓<br>P(1) = −2+16−24 = −10 &lt; 0 ✓<br>P(7) = −98+112−24 = −10 &lt; 0 ✓</div></div>
        <div class="feedback" id="fb-2-fail"><strong>Not quite.</strong> Find the zeros of P(t) = 0 first: −2t²+16t−24 = 0 → t²−8t+12 = 0 → (t−2)(t−6) = 0 → t=2 or t=6. Since the parabola opens downward (−2t²), P is positive BETWEEN the roots.<div class="fb-work">Positive between roots: 2 &lt; t &lt; 6</div></div>
        <button class="btn-check" id="btn-2" onclick="check(2,'B')" disabled>Check answer</button>
      </div>
    </div>
  </div>
</div>

