<div class="tag">SAT Math · Module 4 · Lesson 4.1</div>
<div class="lesson-title">Linear Equations & Graphs</div>
<div class="lesson-sub">Build on Module 3 linear foundations — now with calculator support for more complex coefficients, larger numbers, and real-world data problems that the SAT puts in the calculator section.</div>
<div class="dur-row"><span><b>12 min</b> read</span><span><b>3</b> practice questions</span><span><b>+20 pts</b> on completion</span></div>

<div class="card">
  <div class="sec-title">What changes in the calculator section</div>
  <div class="body-text">The concepts are the same as Module 3 — but the numbers are messier, the contexts are richer, and the problems are often multi-step. The calculator lets you handle arithmetic quickly so you can focus on the reasoning.</div>
  <div class="formula-box">
    <div class="formula">y = mx + b</div>
    <div class="formula-sub">slope m = (y₂ − y₁) / (x₂ − x₁) · y-intercept b = y when x = 0</div>
  </div>
  <table class="concept-table">
    <tr><th>Situation</th><th>What to find</th><th>Method</th></tr>
    <tr><td>Given two points</td><td>Slope and equation</td><td><em>m = Δy/Δx</em>, then solve for b using one point</td></tr>
    <tr><td>Given slope + one point</td><td>Full equation</td><td>Substitute into <em>y = mx + b</em> and solve for b</td></tr>
    <tr><td>Given standard form Ax + By = C</td><td>Slope and intercepts</td><td>Solve for y to get slope-intercept; set y=0 for x-intercept</td></tr>
    <tr><td>Given a table of values</td><td>Rate of change + equation</td><td>Pick two rows, compute slope, then find b</td></tr>
    <tr><td>Word problem with rate and start</td><td>Build the linear model</td><td>Identify slope (rate) and y-intercept (starting value)</td></tr>
  </table>
  <div class="example-box">
    <div class="example-label">Worked example — real-world linear model</div>
    <div class="example-text">
      A plumber charges a $75 call-out fee plus $55 per hour. A competing plumber charges $45 per hour with a $95 call-out fee. After how many hours do they charge the same total?<br><br>
      <span class="fb-work">Plumber 1: C₁ = 75 + 55h</span><br>
      <span class="fb-work">Plumber 2: C₂ = 95 + 45h</span><br>
      <span class="fb-work">Set equal: 75 + 55h = 95 + 45h</span><br>
      <span class="fb-work">10h = 20 → h = 2 hours</span><br>
      Check: C₁(2) = 75+110 = $185 · C₂(2) = 95+90 = $185 ✓
    </div>
  </div>
</div>

<div class="card">
  <div class="sec-title">SAT strategy tips</div>
  <div class="tips-grid">
    <div class="tip"><div class="tip-title">Let the calculator handle arithmetic, not reasoning</div><div class="tip-body">Set up the equation or system first — on paper, not in the calculator. Then use the calculator only to evaluate expressions or solve for exact values. Students who rely on guess-and-check lose time.</div></div>
    <div class="tip"><div class="tip-title">Check units in real-world problems</div><div class="tip-body">If the question gives rates in different time units (hours vs. minutes), convert first. Slope has units of (y-units per x-unit) — state them explicitly when interpreting a linear model in context.</div></div>
    <div class="tip"><div class="tip-title">Identify slope and intercept from word problems</div><div class="tip-body">The rate (per hour, per item, per mile) is always the slope. The fixed cost, starting value, or initial amount is always the y-intercept. Label both before writing the equation.</div></div>
    <div class="tip"><div class="tip-title">Two equations from two conditions</div><div class="tip-body">If a word problem gives two separate conditions, write one equation per condition. Then solve the system. This is the most reliable approach for any "two unknowns" word problem.</div></div>
