<div class="card">
  <div class="sec-title">Key exponential formulas for the SAT</div>
  <div class="formula-box">
    <div class="formula">
      f(t) = a · bᵗ &nbsp;&nbsp; [basic exponential]<br>
      A = P(1 + r/n)ⁿᵗ &nbsp;&nbsp; [compound interest]<br>
      A = Pe^(rt) &nbsp;&nbsp; [continuous compounding]<br>
      f(t) = a · (1/2)^(t/h) &nbsp;&nbsp; [half-life]
    </div>
    <div class="formula-sub">a = initial value · r = rate · n = compoundings per year · t = time · h = half-life period</div>
  </div>
  <table class="interp-table">
    <tr><th>Context</th><th>Model</th><th>Key interpretation</th></tr>
    <tr><td>Compound interest</td><td>A = P(1 + r/n)ⁿᵗ</td><td>P = principal, r = annual rate (decimal), n = times compounded per year, t = years</td></tr>
    <tr><td>Annual growth/decay</td><td>f(t) = a·bᵗ</td><td>b = 1+r for growth, b = 1−r for decay. t = number of years.</td></tr>
    <tr><td>Half-life</td><td>f(t) = a·(0.5)^(t/h)</td><td>After each half-life h, half the substance remains. t/h = number of half-lives elapsed.</td></tr>
    <tr><td>Doubling time</td><td>f(t) = a·2^(t/d)</td><td>After each doubling period d, quantity doubles. t/d = number of doubling periods.</td></tr>
  </table>
  <div class="example-box">
    <div class="example-label">Worked example — compound interest</div>
    <div class="example-text">
      $5,000 is invested at 4.8% annual interest compounded monthly. What is the value after 6 years?<br><br>
      <span class="fb-work">A = P(1 + r/n)ⁿᵗ</span><br>
      <span class="fb-work">= 5000(1 + 0.048/12)^(12×6)</span><br>
      <span class="fb-work">= 5000(1.004)^72</span><br>
      <span class="fb-work">= 5000 × 1.3385 ≈ $6,692.60</span><br><br>
      Use calculator: 5000 × (1.004)^72 = $6,692.61
    </div>
  </div>
</div>

<div class="card">
