    <div class="tip"><div class="tip-title">Half-life: count periods, not raw time</div><div class="tip-body">For half-life problems, compute t/h (number of half-life periods elapsed) as the exponent. If half-life is 5 years and t = 20 years: 20/5 = 4 half-lives → remaining fraction = (1/2)⁴ = 1/16.</div></div>
    <div class="tip"><div class="tip-title">Annual vs. monthly vs. continuous</div><div class="tip-body">Annual compounding: n = 1. Monthly: n = 12. Daily: n = 365. Continuous: A = Peʳᵗ. More frequent compounding always yields slightly more — but the difference diminishes as n increases.</div></div>
    <div class="tip"><div class="tip-title">Build the model from context clues</div><div class="tip-body">"Grows by 7% each year" → b = 1.07. "Loses 15% of its value per year" → b = 0.85. "Population doubles every 8 years" → f(t) = a·2^(t/8). Always extract b from the rate before evaluating.</div></div>
