      <div class="problem-text">A radioactive substance has a half-life of 12 years. A sample currently contains 480 grams.</div>
      <div class="hint">After each 12-year half-life, half the substance remains. In 36 years, there are 36/12 = 3 half-lives. Multiply by (1/2) three times: 480 × (1/2)³.</div>
    </div>
    <div class="q-panel-inner">
      <div class="q-label">Question 1 · Half-Life</div>
      <div class="q-text">How many grams will remain after <strong>36 years</strong>?</div>
      <div class="opts" id="opts-0">
        <div class="opt" onclick="pick(0,this,'A')"><span class="opt-l">A</span>120 grams</div>
        <div class="opt" onclick="pick(0,this,'B')"><span class="opt-l">B</span>60 grams</div>
        <div class="opt" onclick="pick(0,this,'C')"><span class="opt-l">C</span>40 grams</div>
        <div class="opt" onclick="pick(0,this,'D')"><span class="opt-l">D</span>30 grams</div>
      </div>
      <div class="q-actions">
        <div class="feedback" id="fb-0-ok"><strong>Correct! 60 grams</strong><div class="fb-work">Half-lives elapsed: 36/12 = 3<br>Remaining: 480 × (1/2)³ = 480 × 1/8 = 60 grams ✓<br><br>Or step by step:<br>After 12 yr: 240g · After 24 yr: 120g · After 36 yr: 60g ✓</div></div>
        <div class="feedback" id="fb-0-fail"><strong>Not quite.</strong> Count half-life periods: 36 ÷ 12 = 3 periods. Each period halves the amount: 480 × (1/2)³.<div class="fb-work">480 × 1/8 = 60 grams</div></div>
