<div class="lesson-title">Geometry Fundamentals</div>
<div class="lesson-sub">Master the area and perimeter formulas for all shapes on the SAT, angle relationships, and the coordinate geometry connection — all applied to real-world and multi-step problems.</div>
<div class="dur-row"><span><b>13 min</b> read</span><span><b>3</b> practice questions</span><span><b>+20 pts</b> on completion</span></div>

<div class="card">
  <div class="sec-title">Essential area & perimeter formulas</div>
  <div class="formulas-grid">
    <div class="formula-card">
      <div class="formula-shape">Rectangle</div>
      <div class="formula-eq">A = lw · P = 2l + 2w</div>
      <div class="formula-note">l = length, w = width</div>
    </div>
    <div class="formula-card">
      <div class="formula-shape">Triangle</div>
      <div class="formula-eq">A = ½bh</div>
      <div class="formula-note">b = base, h = perpendicular height (not slant side)</div>
    </div>
    <div class="formula-card">
      <div class="formula-shape">Circle</div>
      <div class="formula-eq">A = πr² · C = 2πr</div>
      <div class="formula-note">r = radius. Diameter d = 2r.</div>
    </div>
    <div class="formula-card">
      <div class="formula-shape">Trapezoid</div>
      <div class="formula-eq">A = ½(b₁ + b₂)h</div>
      <div class="formula-note">b₁ and b₂ = parallel bases, h = perpendicular height</div>
    </div>
    <div class="formula-card">
      <div class="formula-shape">Sector of a circle</div>
      <div class="formula-eq">A = (θ/360)πr²</div>
      <div class="formula-note">θ = central angle in degrees. Arc length = (θ/360)·2πr</div>
    </div>
    <div class="formula-card">
      <div class="formula-shape">Composite shapes</div>
      <div class="formula-eq">A_total = sum of parts</div>
      <div class="formula-note">Break complex shapes into rectangles, triangles, and semicircles. Add or subtract areas.</div>
    </div>
  </div>
</div>

<div class="card">
  <div class="sec-title">Angle relationships</div>
  <div class="angle-grid">
    <div class="angle-card">
      <div class="angle-title">Supplementary angles</div>
      <div class="angle-rule">Two angles on a straight line. Sum = 180°.</div>
    </div>
    <div class="angle-card">
      <div class="angle-title">Vertical angles</div>
      <div class="angle-rule">Opposite angles at an intersection. Always equal.</div>
    </div>
    <div class="angle-card">
      <div class="angle-title">Triangle angle sum</div>
      <div class="angle-rule">Three interior angles of any triangle sum to 180°.</div>
    </div>
    <div class="angle-card">
      <div class="angle-title">Parallel lines cut by transversal</div>
      <div class="angle-rule">Alternate interior angles are equal. Co-interior angles sum to 180°.</div>
    </div>
    <div class="angle-card">
      <div class="angle-title">Exterior angle of triangle</div>
      <div class="angle-rule">Equals the sum of the two non-adjacent interior angles.</div>
    </div>
    <div class="angle-card">
      <div class="angle-title">Polygon interior angles</div>
      <div class="angle-rule">Sum = (n − 2) × 180° where n = number of sides.</div>
    </div>
  </div>
  <div class="example-box">
    <div class="example-label">Worked example — composite area</div>
    <div class="example-text">
      A window consists of a rectangle (6 ft wide, 4 ft tall) topped by a semicircle. Find the total area.<br><br>
      <span class="fb-work">Rectangle area = 6 × 4 = 24 sq ft</span><br>
      <span class="fb-work">Semicircle radius = 6/2 = 3 ft</span><br>
      <span class="fb-work">Semicircle area = ½π(3)² = 4.5π ≈ 14.14 sq ft</span><br>
      <span class="fb-work">Total = 24 + 4.5π ≈ 38.14 sq ft</span>
    </div>
  </div>
</div>

<div class="card">
  <div class="sec-title">SAT strategy tips</div>
  <div class="tips-grid">
    <div class="tip"><div class="tip-title">Label every measurement on the figure</div><div class="tip-body">Before computing, write all known measurements on the diagram. Mark right angles, equal sides, and parallel lines. This visual organization prevents missing a given value or using the wrong dimension.</div></div>
    <div class="tip"><div class="tip-title">Height ≠ slant side in triangles</div><div class="tip-body">In A = ½bh, h is the perpendicular height from base to opposite vertex — not the length of a slanted side. If only the slant side is given, use the Pythagorean theorem to find the height first.</div></div>
    <div class="tip"><div class="tip-title">Composite shapes: add or subtract</div><div class="tip-body">For complex shapes, identify which simpler shapes to combine. Sometimes it's easier to find the area of a large shape and subtract the "missing" pieces rather than adding small pieces.</div></div>
    <div class="tip"><div class="tip-title">Sector problems: always use the fraction θ/360</div><div class="tip-body">A sector is a "pizza slice" of a circle. Its area and arc length are both fractions of the full circle — multiply the full-circle formula by θ/360. This works for any angle, not just 90° or 180°.</div></div>
  </div>
</div>

<div class="sec-title" style="margin-bottom:.75rem">Practice questions</div>
