<div class="tag">SAT Math · Module 4 · Lesson 4.6</div>
<div class="lesson-title">Triangles & Pythagorean Theorem</div>
<div class="lesson-sub">Master the Pythagorean theorem, the two special right triangles, similar triangles, and the triangle inequality — the geometry tools the SAT uses most frequently.</div>
<div class="dur-row"><span><b>13 min</b> read</span><span><b>3</b> practice questions</span><span><b>+20 pts</b> on completion</span></div>

<div class="card">
  <div class="sec-title">The Pythagorean theorem and common triples</div>
  <div class="formula-box">
    <div class="formula">a² + b² = c²</div>
    <div class="formula-sub">where c is the hypotenuse (side opposite the right angle) and a, b are the two legs</div>
  </div>
  <div class="body-text">The most important Pythagorean triples to memorize — they appear constantly on the SAT and save calculation time:</div>
  <div class="triangles-grid" style="margin-top:0.75rem;">
    <div class="tri-card">
      <div class="tri-title">3-4-5</div>
      <div class="tri-ratios">3, 4, 5<br>6, 8, 10<br>9, 12, 15<br>5, 12, 13</div>
      <div class="tri-body">Multiples also work. Check: is the ratio of legs 3:4?</div>
    </div>
    <div class="tri-card">
      <div class="tri-title">45-45-90</div>
      <div class="tri-ratios">legs: x, x<br>hypotenuse: x√2</div>
      <div class="tri-body">Isosceles right triangle. Half a square. Hypotenuse = leg × √2.</div>
    </div>
    <div class="tri-card">
      <div class="tri-title">30-60-90</div>
      <div class="tri-ratios">short leg: x<br>long leg: x√3<br>hypotenuse: 2x</div>
      <div class="tri-body">Half an equilateral triangle. Hypotenuse is always double the short leg.</div>
    </div>
  </div>
</div>

<div class="card">
  <div class="sec-title">Similar triangles</div>
  <div class="body-text">Two triangles are <strong>similar</strong> if their angles are equal. Similar triangles have proportional sides — the ratio of any pair of corresponding sides is the same (the scale factor).</div>
  <div class="example-box">
    <div class="example-label">Key similarity conditions</div>
    <div class="example-text">
      <strong>AA (Angle-Angle):</strong> Two pairs of equal angles → triangles are similar.<br>
      <strong>Parallel line in triangle:</strong> A line parallel to one side creates a smaller similar triangle at the top.<br><br>
      <strong>Setting up proportions:</strong> If △ABC ~ △DEF, then:<br>
      <span class="fb-work">AB/DE = BC/EF = AC/DF = scale factor k</span><br><br>
      <strong>Area ratio:</strong> If side lengths are in ratio k:1, then areas are in ratio k²:1.
    </div>
  </div>
  <div class="example-box" style="margin-top:.75rem;">
    <div class="example-label">Worked example — similar triangles with parallel lines</div>
    <div class="example-text">
      A 6-foot person casts a 4-foot shadow. At the same time, a tree casts a 22-foot shadow. How tall is the tree?<br><br>
      <span class="fb-work">Person/shadow = tree/shadow: 6/4 = h/22</span><br>
      <span class="fb-work">4h = 132 → h = 33 feet</span>
    </div>
  </div>
</div>

<div class="card">
  <div class="sec-title">SAT strategy tips</div>
  <div class="tips-grid">
    <div class="tip"><div class="tip-title">Recognize Pythagorean triples instantly</div><div class="tip-body">Before computing a² + b², check if the sides are a multiple of 3-4-5 or 5-12-13. If legs are 9 and 12: that's 3×(3-4-5) → hypotenuse = 15. This saves 30+ seconds per problem.</div></div>
    <div class="tip"><div class="tip-title">30-60-90: hypotenuse is always 2× short leg</div><div class="tip-body">If you know the hypotenuse, the short leg is half of it. The long leg is short leg × √3. Never mix these up — the short leg is opposite the 30° angle, the long leg is opposite the 60° angle.</div></div>
    <div class="tip"><div class="tip-title">Similar triangles: set up ratios carefully</div><div class="tip-body">When setting up proportions, match corresponding sides — the sides opposite equal angles. Label the triangles with their angle measures first, then pair up the sides that face the same angle.</div></div>
    <div class="tip"><div class="tip-title">Triangle inequality: sum of any two sides > third</div><div class="tip-body">In any triangle, the sum of any two sides must be greater than the third side. The SAT uses this to test whether a given set of measurements can form a valid triangle.</div></div>
  </div>
</div>

<div class="sec-title" style="margin-bottom:.75rem">Practice questions</div>
<div class="q-tabs">
  <button class="q-tab active" onclick="switchQ(0,this)">Question 1</button>
  <button class="q-tab" onclick="switchQ(1,this)">Question 2</button>
  <button class="q-tab" onclick="switchQ(2,this)">Question 3</button>
</div>

<div class="q-panel active" id="qp-0">
  <div class="math-layout">
    <div class="problem-panel">
      <div class="panel-label">Problem</div>
      <div class="problem-text">A right triangle has legs of length 5 and 12.</div>
      <div class="hint">Check: is 5-12-? a Pythagorean triple? Yes — 5, 12, 13 is a well-known triple. No calculation needed if you recognize it. Otherwise: c² = 5² + 12² = 25 + 144 = 169 → c = 13.</div>
    </div>
    <div class="q-panel-inner">
      <div class="q-label">Question 1 · Pythagorean Theorem</div>
      <div class="q-text">What is the length of the <strong>hypotenuse</strong>?</div>
      <div class="opts" id="opts-0">
        <div class="opt" onclick="pick(0,this,'A')"><span class="opt-l">A</span>√119</div>
        <div class="opt" onclick="pick(0,this,'B')"><span class="opt-l">B</span>13</div>
        <div class="opt" onclick="pick(0,this,'C')"><span class="opt-l">C</span>17</div>
        <div class="opt" onclick="pick(0,this,'D')"><span class="opt-l">D</span>√17</div>
      </div>
      <div class="q-actions">
        <div class="feedback" id="fb-0-ok"><strong>Correct! 13</strong><div class="fb-work">c² = 5² + 12² = 25 + 144 = 169<br>c = √169 = 13<br><br>5-12-13 is a classic Pythagorean triple — memorize it! ✓</div></div>
        <div class="feedback" id="fb-0-fail"><strong>Not quite.</strong> Use a² + b² = c²: 5² + 12² = 25 + 144 = 169. Take the square root.<div class="fb-work">√169 = 13 (5-12-13 triple)</div></div>
        <button class="btn-check" id="btn-0" onclick="check(0,'B')" disabled>Check answer</button>
      </div>
    </div>
  </div>
</div>

<div class="q-panel" id="qp-1">
  <div class="math-layout">
    <div class="problem-panel">
      <div class="panel-label">Problem</div>
      <div class="problem-text">In a 30-60-90 triangle, the hypotenuse has length 18.</div>
      <div class="hint">In a 30-60-90 triangle: hypotenuse = 2 × short leg. So short leg = 18/2 = 9. Long leg = short leg × √3 = 9√3.</div>
    </div>
    <div class="q-panel-inner">
      <div class="q-label">Question 2 · Special Right Triangles</div>
      <div class="q-text">What is the length of the <strong>longer leg</strong>?</div>
      <div class="opts" id="opts-1">
        <div class="opt" onclick="pick(1,this,'A')"><span class="opt-l">A</span>9</div>
        <div class="opt" onclick="pick(1,this,'B')"><span class="opt-l">B</span>9√2</div>
        <div class="opt" onclick="pick(1,this,'C')"><span class="opt-l">C</span>9√3</div>
        <div class="opt" onclick="pick(1,this,'D')"><span class="opt-l">D</span>18√3</div>
      </div>
      <div class="q-actions">
        <div class="feedback" id="fb-1-ok"><strong>Correct! 9√3</strong><div class="fb-work">30-60-90 ratios: short leg : long leg : hypotenuse = x : x√3 : 2x<br>Hypotenuse = 18 = 2x → x = 9 (short leg)<br>Long leg = 9√3 ✓<br><br>Option A (9) is the SHORT leg.<br>Option B (9√2) would apply to a 45-45-90 triangle, not 30-60-90.</div></div>
        <div class="feedback" id="fb-1-fail"><strong>Not quite.</strong> In 30-60-90: hypotenuse = 2 × short leg → short leg = 9. Long leg = short leg × √3.<div class="fb-work">Long leg = 9√3</div></div>
        <button class="btn-check" id="btn-1" onclick="check(1,'C')" disabled>Check answer</button>
      </div>
    </div>
  </div>
</div>

<div class="q-panel" id="qp-2">
  <div class="math-layout">
    <div class="problem-panel">
      <div class="panel-label">Problem</div>
      <div class="problem-text">Two similar triangles have corresponding sides in the ratio 3:5. The area of the smaller triangle is 27 cm².</div>
      <div class="hint">If sides are in ratio k:1, areas are in ratio k²:1. Here k = 5/3. Area ratio = (5/3)² = 25/9. Larger area = 27 × (25/9).</div>
    </div>
    <div class="q-panel-inner">
      <div class="q-label">Question 3 · Similar Triangles</div>
      <div class="q-text">What is the area of the <strong>larger triangle</strong>?</div>
      <div class="opts" id="opts-2">
        <div class="opt" onclick="pick(2,this,'A')"><span class="opt-l">A</span>45 cm²</div>
        <div class="opt" onclick="pick(2,this,'B')"><span class="opt-l">B</span>75 cm²</div>
        <div class="opt" onclick="pick(2,this,'C')"><span class="opt-l">C</span>135 cm²</div>
        <div class="opt" onclick="pick(2,this,'D')"><span class="opt-l">D</span>81 cm²</div>
      </div>
      <div class="q-actions">
        <div class="feedback" id="fb-2-ok"><strong>Correct! 75 cm²</strong><div class="fb-work">Side ratio = 3:5 → area ratio = 3²:5² = 9:25<br>Larger area = 27 × (25/9) = 27 × 25/9 = 675/9 = 75 cm² ✓</div></div>
        <div class="feedback" id="fb-2-fail"><strong>Not quite.</strong> Areas scale as the square of the side ratio. Side ratio 3:5 → area ratio 9:25. Larger area = 27 × (25/9).<div class="fb-work">27 × 25/9 = 75 cm²</div></div>
        <button class="btn-check" id="btn-2" onclick="check(2,'B')" disabled>Check answer</button>
      </div>
    </div>
  </div>
</div>

